{"title_page": "H3K36 Methylation", "text_new": "'''H3K36me''' is an [[epigenetic]] modification to the DNA packaging protein [[Histone H3]], specifically, the mono-[[methylation]] at the 36th [[lysine]] residue of the histone H3 protein.\n\nThere are diverse modifications at H3K36, such as phosphorylation, methylation, acetylation and ubiquitylation, which have many important biological processes.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wagner EJ, Carpenter PB | title = Understanding the language of Lys36 methylation at histone H3 | journal = Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 115\u201326 | date = January 2012 | pmid = 22266761 | pmc = 3969746 | doi = 10.1038/nrm3274 }}</ref> The methylation of H3K36 has particularly had effects in transcriptional repression, alternative splicing, dosage compensation, DNA replication and repair, DNA methylation and the transmission of the memory of gene expression from parents to offspring during development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Nomenclature ==\nH3K36me2 indicates [[Methylation|monomethylation]] of [[lysine]] 36 on histone H3 protein subunit:<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Blakey CA, Litt MD | chapter = Chapter 2 - Histone modifications\u2014models and mechanisms | veditors = Huang S, Litt MD, Blakey CA |title=Epigenetic Gene Expression and Regulation | location = London | publisher = Elsevier/Academic Press |date=2015-11-30  |pages=21\u201338 | doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-799958-6.00002-0 |isbn=978-0-12-799958-6 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Abbr.\n|Meaning\n|-\n|H3\n|H3 family of histones\n|-\n|K\n|standard abbreviation for lysine\n|-\n|36\n|position of amino acid residue\n(counting from N-terminus)\n|-\n|me\n|methyl group\n|-\n|1\n|number of methyl groups added\n|}\n\n== Lysine methylation ==\n[[File:Methylation-lysine.PNG|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Methylation-lysine.PNG|frameless|591x591px|alt=]]\n\nThis diagram shows the progressive methylation of a lysine residue. The mono-methylation denotes the methylation present in H3K36me3.\n\nLysine methylation is the addition of a methyl group to the lysine of histone proteins.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wang Z, Liu H | title = Lysine methylation regulates nervous system diseases | journal = Neuropeptides | volume = 76 | pages = 101929 | date = August 2019 | pmid = 31076097 | doi = 10.1016/j.npep.2019.04.004 | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0143417918301574 }}</ref> This occurs via histone lysine methyltransferses (HMTase) that utilize ''S''-adenosylmethionine in order to specifically place the methyl group on histone Lys or Arg residues.<ref name=\":0\" /> So far, there has only been eight specific mammalian enzymes discovered that are able to methylate H3K36 in vitro and/or in vivo, all of which have identical catalytic SET domains but, different preferaces for Lys36 residues in different methylation states.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Histone modifications ==\nThe genomic DNA of eukaryotic cells is wrapped around special protein molecules known as [[histones]]. The complexes formed by the looping of the DNA are known as [[chromatin]]. The basic structural unit of chromatin is the [[nucleosome]], which consists of the core octamer of histones ([[Histone H2A|H2A]], [[Histone H2B|H2B]], [[Histone H3|H3]] and [[Histone H4|H4]]) as well as a linker histone and about 180 base pairs of DNA wrapped around it. These core histones are rich in lysine and arginine residues. The carboxyl (C) terminal end of these histones contribute to histone-histone interactions, as well as histone-DNA interactions. The amino (N) terminal charged tails are the site of the post-translational modifications, such as the one seen in H3K36me3.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ruthenburg AJ, Li H, Patel DJ, Allis CD | title = Multivalent engagement of chromatin modifications by linked binding modules | journal = Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology | volume = 8 | issue = 12 | pages = 983\u201394 | date = December 2007 | pmid = 18037899 | pmc = 4690530 | doi = 10.1038/nrm2298 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kouzarides T | title = Chromatin modifications and their function | journal = Cell | volume = 128 | issue = 4 | pages = 693\u2013705 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17320507 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2007.02.005 }}</ref>\n\n== Epigenetic implications ==\nThe post-translational modification of histone tails by either histone modifying complexes or chromatin remodelling complexes are interpreted by the cell and lead to complex, combinatorial transcriptional output. It is thought that a [[histone code]] dictates the expression of genes by a complex interaction between the histones in a particular region.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Jenuwein T, Allis CD | title = Translating the histone code | journal = Science | volume = 293 | issue = 5532 | pages = 1074\u201380 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11498575 | doi = 10.1126/science.1063127 }}</ref> The current understanding and interpretation of histones comes from two large scale projects: [[ENCODE]] and the Epigenomic roadmap.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Birney E, Stamatoyannopoulos JA, Dutta A, Guig\u00f3 R, Gingeras TR, Margulies EH, etal | collaboration = ENCODE Project Consortium | title = Identification and analysis of functional elements in 1% of the human genome by the ENCODE pilot project | journal = Nature | volume = 447 | issue = 7146 | pages = 799\u2013816 | date = June 2007 | pmid = 17571346 | pmc = 2212820 | doi = 10.1038/nature05874 | bibcode = 2007Natur.447..799B }}</ref> The purpose of the epigenomic study was to investigate epigenetic changes across the entire genome. This led to chromatin states which define genomic regions by grouping the interactions of different proteins and/or histone modifications together. Chromatin states were investigated in [[Drosophila melanogaster|Drosophila]] cells by looking at the binding location of proteins in the genome. Use of [[ChIP-sequencing]] revealed regions in the genome characterized by different banding.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Filion GJ, van Bemmel JG, Braunschweig U, Talhout W, Kind J, Ward LD, Brugman W, de Castro IJ, Kerkhoven RM, Bussemaker HJ, van Steensel B | display-authors = 6 | title = Systematic protein location mapping reveals five principal chromatin types in Drosophila cells | journal = Cell | volume = 143 | issue = 2 | pages = 212\u201324 | date = October 2010 | pmid = 20888037 | pmc = 3119929 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2010.09.009 }}</ref> Different developmental stages were profiled in Drosophila as well, an emphasis was placed on histone modification relevance.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Roy S, Ernst J, Kharchenko PV, Kheradpour P, Negre N, Eaton ML, etal | collaboration = modENCODE Consortium | title = Identification of functional elements and regulatory circuits by Drosophila modENCODE | journal = Science | volume = 330 | issue = 6012 | pages = 1787\u201397 | date = December 2010 | pmid = 21177974 | pmc = 3192495 | doi = 10.1126/science.1198374 | bibcode = 2010Sci...330.1787R }}</ref> A look in to the data obtained led to the definition of chromatin states based on histone modifications.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kharchenko PV, Alekseyenko AA, Schwartz YB, Minoda A, Riddle NC, Ernst J, Sabo PJ, Larschan E, Gorchakov AA, Gu T, Linder-Basso D, Plachetka A, Shanower G, Tolstorukov MY, Luquette LJ, Xi R, Jung YL, Park RW, Bishop EP, Canfield TK, Sandstrom R, Thurman RE, MacAlpine DM, Stamatoyannopoulos JA, Kellis M, Elgin SC, Kuroda MI, Pirrotta V, Karpen GH, Park PJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Comprehensive analysis of the chromatin landscape in Drosophila melanogaster | journal = Nature | volume = 471 | issue = 7339 | pages = 480\u20135 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21179089 | pmc = 3109908 | doi = 10.1038/nature09725 | bibcode = 2011Natur.471..480K }}</ref> Certain modifications were mapped and enrichment was seen to localize in certain genomic regions. Five core histone modifications were found with each respective one being linked to various cell functions.\n\n* [[H3K4me3]]-promoters\n* [[H3K4me1]]- primed enhancers\n* H3K36me3-gene bodies\n* [[H3K27me3]]-[[Polycomb-group proteins|polycomb]] repression\n* [[H3K9me3]]-[[heterochromatin]]\n\nThe human genome was annotated with chromatin states. These annotated states can be used as new ways to annotate a genome independently of the underlying genome sequence. This independence from the DNA sequence enforces the epigenetic nature of histone modifications. Chromatin states are also useful in identifying regulatory elements that have no defined sequence, such as enhancers. This additional level of annotation allows for a deeper understanding of cell specific gene regulation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kundaje A, Meuleman W, Ernst J, Bilenky M, Yen A, Heravi-Moussavi A, etal | collaboration = Roadmap Epigenomics Consortium | title = Integrative analysis of 111 reference human epigenomes | journal = Nature | volume = 518 | issue = 7539 | pages = 317\u201330 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25693563 | pmc = 4530010 | doi = 10.1038/nature14248 | bibcode = 2015Natur.518..317. }}</ref>\n\n== Methods ==\nThe histone mark H3K36me can be detected in a variety of ways:\n\n# Chromatin [[Immunoprecipitation]] Sequencing ([[ChIP-sequencing]]) measures the amount of DNA enrichment once bound to a targeted protein and immunoprecipitated. It results in good optimization and is used in vivo to reveal DNA-protein binding occurring in cells. ChIP-Seq can be used to identify and quantify various DNA fragments for different histone modifications along a genomic region.<ref>[https://www.illumina.com/Documents/products/datasheets/datasheet_chip_sequence.pdf \"Whole-Genome Chromatin IP Sequencing (ChIP-Seq)\"](PDF). ''Illumina''. Retrieved 23 October 2019.</ref>\n# Micrococcal Nuclease sequencing (MNase-seq) is used to investigate regions that are bound by well positioned nucleosomes. Use of the micrococcal nuclease enzyme is employed to identify nucleosome positioning. Well positioned [[Nucleosome|nucleosomes]] are seen to have enrichment of sequences.<ref>[https://www.illumina.com/science/sequencing-method-explorer/kits-and-arrays/maine-seq-mnase-seq-nucleo-seq.html?langsel=/us/ \"MAINE-Seq/Mnase-Seq\"]. ''illumina''. Retrieved 23 October2019.</ref>\n# Assay for transposase accessible chromatin sequencing (ATAC-seq) is used to look in to regions that are nucleosome free (open chromatin). It uses hyperactive [[Tn5 transposon]] to highlight nucleosome localisation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Buenrostro JD, Wu B, Chang HY, Greenleaf WJ | title = ATAC-seq: A Method for Assaying Chromatin Accessibility Genome-Wide | journal = Current Protocols in Molecular Biology | volume = 109 | issue = 1 | pages = 21.29.1-21.29.9 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25559105 | pmc = 4374986 | doi = 10.1002/0471142727.mb2129s109 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schep AN, Buenrostro JD, Denny SK, Schwartz K, Sherlock G, Greenleaf WJ | title = Structured nucleosome fingerprints enable high-resolution mapping of chromatin architecture within regulatory regions | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25 | issue = 11 | pages = 1757\u201370 | date = November 2015 | pmid = 26314830 | pmc = 4617971 | doi = 10.1101/gr.192294.115 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Song L, Crawford GE | title = DNase-seq: a high-resolution technique for mapping active gene regulatory elements across the genome from mammalian cells | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Protocols | volume = 2010 | issue = 2 | pages = pdb.prot5384 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20150147 | pmc = 3627383 | doi = 10.1101/pdb.prot5384 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Histone methylation]]\n* [[Histone methyltransferase]]\n* [[Methyllysine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "'''H3K36me''' is an [[epigenetic]] modification to the DNA packaging protein [[Histone H3]], specifically, the mono-[[methylation]] at the 36th [[lysine]] residue of the histone H3 protein.\n\nThere are diverse modifications at H3K36, such as phosphorylation, methylation, acetylation and ubiquitylation, which have many important biological processes.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wagner EJ, Carpenter PB | title = Understanding the language of Lys36 methylation at histone H3 | journal = Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 115\u201326 | date = January 2012 | pmid = 22266761 | pmc = 3969746 | doi = 10.1038/nrm3274 }}</ref> The methylation of H3K36 has particularly had effects in transcriptional repression, alternative splicing, dosage compensation, DNA replication and repair, DNA methylation and the transmission of the memory of gene expression from parents to offspring during development.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Nomenclature ==\nH3K36me2 indicates [[Methylation|monomethylation]] of [[lysine]] 36 on histone H3 protein subunit:<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Blakey CA, Litt MD | chapter = Chapter 2 - Histone modifications\u2014models and mechanisms | veditors = Huang S, Litt MD, Blakey CA |title=Epigenetic Gene Expression and Regulation | location = London | publisher = Elsevier/Academic Press |date=2015-11-30  |pages=21\u201338 | doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-799958-6.00002-0 |isbn=978-0-12-799958-6 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Abbr.\n|Meaning\n|-\n|H3\n|H3 family of histones\n|-\n|K\n|standard abbreviation for lysine\n|-\n|36\n|position of amino acid residue\n(counting from N-terminus)\n|-\n|me\n|methyl group\n|-\n|1\n|number of methyl groups added\n|}\n\n== Lysine methylation ==\n[[File:Methylation-lysine.PNG|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Methylation-lysine.PNG|frameless|591x591px|alt=]]\n\nThis diagram shows the progressive methylation of a lysine residue. The mono-methylation denotes the methylation present in H3K36me3.\n\nLysine methylation is the addition of a methyl group to the lysine of histone proteins.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wang Z, Liu H | title = Lysine methylation regulates nervous system diseases | journal = Neuropeptides | volume = 76 | pages = 101929 | date = August 2019 | pmid = 31076097 | doi = 10.1016/j.npep.2019.04.004 | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0143417918301574 }}</ref> This occurs via histone lysine methyltransferses (HMTase) that utilize ''S''-adenosylmethionine in order to specifically place the methyl group on histone Lys or Arg residues.<ref name=\":0\" /> So far, there has only been eight specific mammalian enzymes discovered that are able to methylate H3K36 in vitro and/or in vivo, all of which have identical catalytic SET domains but, different preferaces for Lys36 residues in different methylation states.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Histone modifications ==\nThe genomic DNA of eukaryotic cells is wrapped around special protein molecules known as [[histones]]. The complexes formed by the looping of the DNA are known as [[chromatin]]. The basic structural unit of chromatin is the [[nucleosome]], which consists of the core octamer of histones ([[Histone H2A|H2A]], [[Histone H2B|H2B]], [[Histone H3|H3]] and [[Histone H4|H4]]) as well as a linker histone and about 180 base pairs of DNA wrapped around it. These core histones are rich in lysine and arginine residues. The carboxyl (C) terminal end of these histones contribute to histone-histone interactions, as well as histone-DNA interactions. The amino (N) terminal charged tails are the site of the post-translational modifications, such as the one seen in H3K36me3.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ruthenburg AJ, Li H, Patel DJ, Allis CD | title = Multivalent engagement of chromatin modifications by linked binding modules | journal = Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology | volume = 8 | issue = 12 | pages = 983\u201394 | date = December 2007 | pmid = 18037899 | pmc = 4690530 | doi = 10.1038/nrm2298 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kouzarides T | title = Chromatin modifications and their function | journal = Cell | volume = 128 | issue = 4 | pages = 693\u2013705 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17320507 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2007.02.005 }}</ref>\n\n== Epigenetic implications ==\nThe post-translational modification of histone tails by either histone modifying complexes or chromatin remodelling complexes are interpreted by the cell and lead to complex, combinatorial transcriptional output. It is thought that a [[histone code]] dictates the expression of genes by a complex interaction between the histones in a particular region.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Jenuwein T, Allis CD | title = Translating the histone code | journal = Science | volume = 293 | issue = 5532 | pages = 1074\u201380 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11498575 | doi = 10.1126/science.1063127 }}</ref> The current understanding and interpretation of histones comes from two large scale projects: [[ENCODE]] and the Epigenomic roadmap.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Birney E, Stamatoyannopoulos JA, Dutta A, Guig\u00f3 R, Gingeras TR, Margulies EH, etal | collaboration = ENCODE Project Consortium | title = Identification and analysis of functional elements in 1% of the human genome by the ENCODE pilot project | journal = Nature | volume = 447 | issue = 7146 | pages = 799\u2013816 | date = June 2007 | pmid = 17571346 | pmc = 2212820 | doi = 10.1038/nature05874 | bibcode = 2007Natur.447..799B }}</ref> The purpose of the epigenomic study was to investigate epigenetic changes across the entire genome. This led to chromatin states which define genomic regions by grouping the interactions of different proteins and/or histone modifications together. Chromatin states were investigated in [[Drosophila melanogaster|Drosophila]] cells by looking at the binding location of proteins in the genome. Use of [[ChIP-sequencing]] revealed regions in the genome characterized by different banding.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Filion GJ, van Bemmel JG, Braunschweig U, Talhout W, Kind J, Ward LD, Brugman W, de Castro IJ, Kerkhoven RM, Bussemaker HJ, van Steensel B | display-authors = 6 | title = Systematic protein location mapping reveals five principal chromatin types in Drosophila cells | journal = Cell | volume = 143 | issue = 2 | pages = 212\u201324 | date = October 2010 | pmid = 20888037 | pmc = 3119929 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2010.09.009 }}</ref> Different developmental stages were profiled in Drosophila as well, an emphasis was placed on histone modification relevance.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Roy S, Ernst J, Kharchenko PV, Kheradpour P, Negre N, Eaton ML, etal | collaboration = modENCODE Consortium | title = Identification of functional elements and regulatory circuits by Drosophila modENCODE | journal = Science | volume = 330 | issue = 6012 | pages = 1787\u201397 | date = December 2010 | pmid = 21177974 | pmc = 3192495 | doi = 10.1126/science.1198374 | bibcode = 2010Sci...330.1787R }}</ref> A look in to the data obtained led to the definition of chromatin states based on histone modifications.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kharchenko PV, Alekseyenko AA, Schwartz YB, Minoda A, Riddle NC, Ernst J, Sabo PJ, Larschan E, Gorchakov AA, Gu T, Linder-Basso D, Plachetka A, Shanower G, Tolstorukov MY, Luquette LJ, Xi R, Jung YL, Park RW, Bishop EP, Canfield TK, Sandstrom R, Thurman RE, MacAlpine DM, Stamatoyannopoulos JA, Kellis M, Elgin SC, Kuroda MI, Pirrotta V, Karpen GH, Park PJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Comprehensive analysis of the chromatin landscape in Drosophila melanogaster | journal = Nature | volume = 471 | issue = 7339 | pages = 480\u20135 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21179089 | pmc = 3109908 | doi = 10.1038/nature09725 | bibcode = 2011Natur.471..480K }}</ref> Certain modifications were mapped and enrichment was seen to localize in certain genomic regions. Five core histone modifications were found with each respective one being linked to various cell functions.\n\n* [[H3K4me3]]-promoters\n* [[H3K4me1]]- primed enhancers\n* H3K36me3-gene bodies\n* [[H3K27me3]]-[[Polycomb-group proteins|polycomb]] repression\n* [[H3K9me3]]-[[heterochromatin]]\n\nThe human genome was annotated with chromatin states. These annotated states can be used as new ways to annotate a genome independently of the underlying genome sequence. This independence from the DNA sequence enforces the epigenetic nature of histone modifications. Chromatin states are also useful in identifying regulatory elements that have no defined sequence, such as enhancers. This additional level of annotation allows for a deeper understanding of cell specific gene regulation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kundaje A, Meuleman W, Ernst J, Bilenky M, Yen A, Heravi-Moussavi A, etal | collaboration = Roadmap Epigenomics Consortium | title = Integrative analysis of 111 reference human epigenomes | journal = Nature | volume = 518 | issue = 7539 | pages = 317\u201330 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25693563 | pmc = 4530010 | doi = 10.1038/nature14248 | bibcode = 2015Natur.518..317. }}</ref>\n\n== Methods ==\nThe histone mark H3K36me can be detected in a variety of ways:\n\n# Chromatin [[Immunoprecipitation]] Sequencing ([[ChIP-sequencing]]) measures the amount of DNA enrichment once bound to a targeted protein and immunoprecipitated. It results in good optimization and is used in vivo to reveal DNA-protein binding occurring in cells. ChIP-Seq can be used to identify and quantify various DNA fragments for different histone modifications along a genomic region.<ref>[https://www.illumina.com/Documents/products/datasheets/datasheet_chip_sequence.pdf \"Whole-Genome Chromatin IP Sequencing (ChIP-Seq)\"](PDF). ''Illumina''. Retrieved 23 October 2019.</ref>\n# Micrococcal Nuclease sequencing (MNase-seq) is used to investigate regions that are bound by well positioned nucleosomes. Use of the micrococcal nuclease enzyme is employed to identify nucleosome positioning. Well positioned [[Nucleosome|nucleosomes]] are seen to have enrichment of sequences.<ref>[https://www.illumina.com/science/sequencing-method-explorer/kits-and-arrays/maine-seq-mnase-seq-nucleo-seq.html?langsel=/us/ \"MAINE-Seq/Mnase-Seq\"]. ''illumina''. Retrieved 23 October2019.</ref>\n# Assay for transposase accessible chromatin sequencing (ATAC-seq) is used to look in to regions that are nucleosome free (open chromatin). It uses hyperactive [[Tn5 transposon]] to highlight nucleosome localisation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Buenrostro JD, Wu B, Chang HY, Greenleaf WJ | title = ATAC-seq: A Method for Assaying Chromatin Accessibility Genome-Wide | journal = Current Protocols in Molecular Biology | volume = 109 | issue = 1 | pages = 21.29.1-21.29.9 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25559105 | pmc = 4374986 | doi = 10.1002/0471142727.mb2129s109 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schep AN, Buenrostro JD, Denny SK, Schwartz K, Sherlock G, Greenleaf WJ | title = Structured nucleosome fingerprints enable high-resolution mapping of chromatin architecture within regulatory regions | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25 | issue = 11 | pages = 1757\u201370 | date = November 2015 | pmid = 26314830 | pmc = 4617971 | doi = 10.1101/gr.192294.115 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Song L, Crawford GE | title = DNase-seq: a high-resolution technique for mapping active gene regulatory elements across the genome from mammalian cells | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Protocols | volume = 2010 | issue = 2 | pages = pdb.prot5384 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20150147 | pmc = 3627383 | doi = 10.1101/pdb.prot5384 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Histone methylation]]\n* [[Histone methyltransferase]]\n* [[Methyllysine]]\n\n== Refrences ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Refrences > References", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H3K36_Methylation"}
{"title_page": "Mary Ann Casey", "text_new": "{{Infobox US Ambassador\n| name= Mary Ann Casey\n| image= \n| imagesize = \n| order=\n| ambassador_from= United States\n| country= Tunisia\n| term_start = July 5, 1994 \n| term_end= July 18, 1997 \n| president= [[Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor = [[John T. McCarthy]]\n| successor = [[Robin Lynn Raphel]]\n\n| ambassador_from2= United States\n| country2= Algeria\n| term_start2 = July 2, 1991 \n| term_end2=  October 19, 1994 \n| president2= [[Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Christopher W.S. Ross]]\n| successor2 = [[Ronald E. Neumann]]\n\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Boulder, Colorado]]\n| spouse= \n| party= \n| profession=[[diplomacy|Diplomat]], [[Diplomatic rank#In the United States Foreign Service|Career Ambassador]]\n| blank1       = \n| data1        = \n| footnotes=\n}}\n{{U.S. Near Eastern Affairs Diplomats}}\n\n'''Mary Ann Casey''' (born November 11, 1949 in [[Boulder, Colorado]])<ref name=\"fas\"/> is a retired career [[Foreign Service Officer]] and U.S. [[United States Ambassador to Algeria|Ambassador to Algeria]] (1991\u20131994)<ref name=\"us\">[https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/po/com/10360.htm United States Department of State - Chiefs of Mission for Algeria list]</ref> and [[Tunisia]] (1994\u20131997).<ref name=\"fas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/irp/news/1994/13233804-13235715.htm|title=USIA News Report|author=US Information Agency|first=|work=US Information Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nAmbassador Casey graduated with a degree in international relations from the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]]<ref name=\"fas\"/> in 1970,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cualum.org/awards/norlin-award-winners/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309062932/https://www.cualum.org/awards/norlin-award-winners/ |archivedate=2012-03-09 }}</ref> and spent most of her overseas career in northern [[Africa]]. Her first assignment was as vice consul and political officer at the U.S. Embassy in [[Morocco]]; her most recent overseas position was [[United States Ambassador to Tunisia|Ambassador to Tunisia]]. In between, she spent time as a Watch Officer in the [[State Department]] [[Executive Secretariat|Operations Center]], desk officer for [[Iraq]], as a [[Hoover Institution]] National Fellow at [[Stanford]], as Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for [[Bureau of Intelligence and Research|Intelligence and Research]], and as the [[United States Ambassador to Algeria|Ambassador to Algeria]].<ref name=\"fas\"/>\n\nUpon returning from Tunisia, Ambassador Casey became the State Department's \"Diplomat in Residence\" at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], where she helped establish the [https://web.archive.org/web/20080402003001/http://www.colorado.edu/oie/ship/ Smith Hall International Program], chaired the International Affairs committee of the University's [[Conference on World Affairs]], and taught several courses on international relations.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\nHer foreign languages include [[Arabic]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\"fas\"/>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://bushlib.tamu.edu/research/finding_aids/pdfs/1998-0260-F.pdf|title=Records on Women Ambassadors|publisher=George Bush Presidential Library}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[United States Ambassador to Algeria|U.S. Ambassador to Algeria]]|before=[[Christopher W.S. Ross]]|after=[[Ronald E. Neumann]]|years=1991&ndash;1994}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[United States Ambassador to Tunisia|U.S. Ambassador to Tunisia]]|before=[[John T. McCarthy]]|after=[[Robin Raphel]]|years=1994&ndash;1997}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casey, Mary Ann}}\n[[Category:People from Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Algeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder faculty]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:United States Foreign Service personnel]]\n[[Category:American women ambassadors]]\n\n\n{{US-diplomat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox US Ambassador\n| name= Mary Ann Casey\n| image= \n| imagesize = \n| order=\n| ambassador_from= United States\n| country= Tunisia\n| term_start = July 5, 1994 \n| term_end= July 18, 1997 \n| president= [[Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor = [[John T. McCarthy]]\n| successor = [[Robin Lynn Raphel]]\n\n| ambassador_from2= United States\n| country2= Algeria\n| term_start2 = July 2, 1991 \n| term_end2=  October 19, 1994 \n| president2= [[Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Christopher W.S. Ross]]\n| successor2 = [[Ronald E. Neumann]]\n\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Boulder, Colorado]]\n| spouse= \n| party= \n| profession=[[diplomacy|Diplomat]], [[Diplomatic rank#In the United States Foreign Service|Career Ambassador]]\n| blank1       = \n| data1        = \n| footnotes=\n}}\n{{U.S. Near Eastern Affairs Diplomats}}\n\n'''Mary Ann Casey''' (born November 11, 1949 in [[Boulder, Colorado]])<ref name=\"fas\"/> is a retired career [[Foreign Service Officer]] and U.S. [[United States Ambassador to Algeria|Ambassador to Algeria]] (1991\u20131994)<ref name=\"us\">[https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/po/com/10360.htm United States Department of State - Chiefs of Mission for Algeria list]</ref> and [[Tunisia]] (1994\u20131997).<ref name=\"fas\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fas.org/irp/news/1994/13233804-13235715.htm\n|title=USIA News Report\n|author=US Information Agency\n|work=US Information Agency\n|date=5/11/94}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nAmbassador Casey graduated with a degree in international relations from the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]]<ref name=\"fas\"/> in 1970,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cualum.org/awards/norlin-award-winners/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309062932/https://www.cualum.org/awards/norlin-award-winners/ |archivedate=2012-03-09 }}</ref> and spent most of her overseas career in northern [[Africa]]. Her first assignment was as vice consul and political officer at the U.S. Embassy in [[Morocco]]; her most recent overseas position was [[United States Ambassador to Tunisia|Ambassador to Tunisia]]. In between, she spent time as a Watch Officer in the [[State Department]] [[Executive Secretariat|Operations Center]], desk officer for [[Iraq]], as a [[Hoover Institution]] National Fellow at [[Stanford]], as Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for [[Bureau of Intelligence and Research|Intelligence and Research]], and as the [[United States Ambassador to Algeria|Ambassador to Algeria]].<ref name=\"fas\"/>\n\nUpon returning from Tunisia, Ambassador Casey became the State Department's \"Diplomat in Residence\" at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], where she helped establish the [https://web.archive.org/web/20080402003001/http://www.colorado.edu/oie/ship/ Smith Hall International Program], chaired the International Affairs committee of the University's [[Conference on World Affairs]], and taught several courses on international relations.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\nHer foreign languages include [[Arabic]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\"fas\"/>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://bushlib.tamu.edu/research/finding_aids/pdfs/1998-0260-F.pdf|title=Records on Women Ambassadors|publisher=George Bush Presidential Library}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[United States Ambassador to Algeria|U.S. Ambassador to Algeria]]|before=[[Christopher W.S. Ross]]|after=[[Ronald E. Neumann]]|years=1991&ndash;1994}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[United States Ambassador to Tunisia|U.S. Ambassador to Tunisia]]|before=[[John T. McCarthy]]|after=[[Robin Raphel]]|years=1994&ndash;1997}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casey, Mary Ann}}\n[[Category:People from Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Algeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder faculty]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:United States Foreign Service personnel]]\n[[Category:American women ambassadors]]\n\n\n{{US-diplomat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "U2books", "label": "safe", "comment": "references fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Ann_Casey"}
{"title_page": "Simmba", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 Indian Hindi-language action film directed by Rohit Shetty}}\n{{distinguish|Simba}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Simmba\n| image          = Simmba poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Rohit Shetty]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n*Rohit Shetty\n*Hiroo Yash Johar\n*[[Karan Johar]]\n*Apoorva Mehta<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/simmba-team-gets-goofy-on-the-sets/articleshow/64707897.cms |title='Simmba' team gets goofy on the sets |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926142157/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/simmba-team-gets-goofy-on-the-sets/articleshow/64707897.cms |archive-date=26 September 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay     = Yunus Sajawal<br>[[Sajid-Farhad|Sajid Samji]]\n| writer         = [[Farhad Samji]]<br>'''Dialogues:'''\n| story          = [[Rohit Shetty]]<br>[[Vakkantham Vamsi]]\n| narrator       = [[Ajay Devgn]]\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ranveer Singh]]|[[Sonu Sood]]|[[Sara Ali Khan]]|[[Ashutosh Rana]]|[[Siddhartha Jadhav]]}}\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Tanishk Bagchi]]<br />Lijo George \u2013 DJ Chetas<br />[[S. Thaman]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Amar Mohile]]<br />Chandan Saxena<br />[[S. Thaman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jomon T. John]]\n| editing        = Bunty Negi\n| studio         = [[Reliance Entertainment]]<br />[[Dharma Productions]]<br /> Rohit Shetty Picturez\n| distributor    = [[Reliance Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2018|12|27|[[United Arab Emirates]]|2018|12|28|[[India]]}}\n| runtime        = 159 minutes<ref name=\"bbfc\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/simmba-2018|title=Simmba {{!}} British Board of Film Classification|website=www.bbfc.co.uk|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n| budget         = {{INR|80\u2013139 [[crore]]|link=yes}}<ref name=\"budget\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.zeebiz.com/india/news-simmba-box-office-collection-prediction-day-1-ranveer-singh-ajay-devgn-rohit-shetty-crossover-film-to-earn-rs-20-crore-analyst-says-77757 |title=Simmba Box Office Collection Prediction: Ranveer Singh, Ajay Devgn set to wow you! Rohit Shetty crossover film set to bag big amount |date=27 December 2018 |website=[[Zee Business]] |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=5568 |title=Simmba \u2013 Movie \u2013 Box Office India |website=Box Office India |access-date=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{estimation}} {{INR}}400.19 crore<ref name=\"box1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office |title=Simmba Box Office Collection till Now |website=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singhs-pizzazz-is-lost-to-a-cliched-womens-rights-saga-that-sidelines-women-5804601.html |title=Simmba movie review: Ranveer Singh's pizzazz is lost to a clich\u00e9d women's rights saga that sidelines women |last=Vetticad |first=Anna MM |date=28 December 2018 |work=[[Firstpost]] |access-date=1 April 2019 |publisher=[[Network 18]] |author-link=Anna M. M. Vetticad}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Simmba''''' is a 2018 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[action film]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=simmba.htm |title=Simmba (2018) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref> directed by [[Rohit Shetty]] and written by Yunus Sajawal and [[Sajid-Farhad]]. The third installment of [[Shetty's Police Universe]], the film was produced by Shetty under his banner Rohit Shetty Picturez and [[Karan Johar]], Hiroo Yash Johar and Apoorva Mehta via [[Dharma Productions]]. [[Reliance Entertainment]] also co-produced and distributed the film. It stars [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Sonu Sood]] and [[Sara Ali Khan]], with [[Ajay Devgn]] reprising his role of Bajirao Singham in an extended cameo role. The film follows Sangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao, a corrupt police officer hailing from the same town as Singham, who is forced to lead a more righteous path after tragedy strikes those near him.\n\nThe film is an official partial remake of  the 2015 [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language film ''[[Temper (film)|Temper]]''.<ref name=\"announced\" /> [[Principal photography]] began in June 2018 with most scenes filmed in [[Goa]] and [[Kolhapur]]; the remaining \nwere shot at [[Hyderabad]] and [[Mehboob Studios]] in [[Mumbai]]. The shooting was wrapped up by early December in the same year. The film's soundtrack was composed by [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George \u2013 DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]], with lyrics written by [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]], [[Rashmi Virag]], [[Kumaar]] and [[Kunaal Verma]]. The soundtrack features remakes of two 1996 songs: \"Aankh Marey\" originally from the film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'', and the [[qawwali]] song \"Tere Bin\" by [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]].\n\n''Simmba'' was released in countries of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] on 27 December 2018. The film was released in India and other international territories on the following day; it was distributed worldwide by [[Reliance Entertainment]]. The film received mixed reviews<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/box-office-update-ranveer-singh-fails-to-beat-ranbir-kapoor-as-the-opening-day-of-simmba-is-no-match-to-sanju/338830 |title=Box Office update: Ranveer Singh fails to beat Ranbir Kapoor as the opening day of Simmba is no match to that of Sanju's {{!}} Entertainment News |website=Times Now |access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>  from critics but became Singh's highest-earning opening film as of 2018 and went on to gross about {{INR|link=yes}}400 crore worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-box-office-day-3-ranveer-singh-breaks-personal-record-film-earns-rs-100-cr-worldwide/story-eo9EmtIgPO9xtXKcVZl9qK.html |title=Simmba box office day 3: Ranveer Singh breaks personal record, film earns Rs 100 cr worldwide |date=31 December 2018 |website=Hindustan Times |access-date=31 December 2018}}</ref> Later, it received the Australian [[Telstra People's Choice Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/india/english/life+and+trendz-epaper-lifntr/vijay+sethupathi+shah+rukh+khan+tabu+win+top+awards+at+iffm+awards+2019-newsid-129867114 |title=Vijay Sethupathi, Shah Rukh Khan, Tabu, win top awards at IFFM Awards 2019 - Life and Trendz &#124; DailyHunt |publisher=M.dailyhunt.in |date= |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao is an [[antihero]]ic orphan from Shivgadh, the same town where Bajirao Singham was raised. He observes how policemen make money in the form of bribes, finding himself motivated to become a police officer, and succeeds. Getting bribes from some local thieves and a jeweller, Simmba enjoys and takes full advantage of the lifestyle of a corrupt cop.\n\nHe is soon transferred to Miramar police station, where he sees Shagun Sathe and falls in love with her at first sight. He meets his fellow policemen and one of his juniors, Nityanand Mohile, who is an honest constable, hesitates to salute Simmba as he's a corrupt cop. To prove his worth in Miramar, he interrupts a pub party run by Durva Yashwant Ranade's brothers, Sadashiv \"Sada\" Ranade and Gaurav \"Giri\" Ranade and demands more money from them, whilst promising that he will let them continue with their illegal activities. Durva agrees and uses Simmba to free a land from an old person Vaaman Rao, who is forced to sign the papers by Simmba. Meanwhile, Simmba develops motherly and sisterly bonds with several women and girls, one of whom happens to be Aakruti Dave, a young woman who reminds Simmba of his teacher.\n\nAakruti files a complaint against Sada and Giri for dealing illicit drugs in their pub and using children as peddlers. Simmba initially ignores this after being pacified by Durva, and Shagun in the meantime falls in love with him. Meanwhile, Aakruti learns about the drug racket in the club and goes there one night with Chotu, a mute boy who's her student. She videotapes by cell phone to show evidence to the police, but is caught by Sada and Giri. Chotu discreetly records Sada and Giri assaulting Aakruti and flees once both of them realise.\n\nAakruti is brutally raped and murdered by Sada and Giri. Chotu tries to tell Akruti's friend Kavya about Akruti being in danger. Kavya whilst being chased by Durva's goons goes to Simmba to file Aakruti's missing complaint. Aakruti is found injured in hospital. Simmba tries to talk to her but she dies, leaving him devastated. Police recover the phone and the video and Durva sends his goons to get the phone from Simmba, who is present, mends his ways, and fights them all. Simmba finally wears his police uniform and seeing this change in him, Mohile finally salutes him as they arrest Sada and Giri. He apologises to Vaaman Rao, and returns the land swindled from him. In the court, Simmba is shocked to find Aakruti's video being deleted. He beats up Durva's friend who gave a false statement in the court, leading to his suspension orders. He decides to kill Sada and Giri before he goes, and plans to show it as an encounter. He shoots them both and shows as if he killed them in an act of self-defence. A SIT committee is set up by the state, who question Simmba's encounter. To achieve clarity to the situation, Home Minister Vinayak Dutta appoints a neutral officer to handle Aakruti's case, as well as Simmba's controversial encounter.\n\nEnraged, Durva and his goons capture Simmba. Suddenly DCP Bajirao Singham comes to his rescue and both of them beat up Durva and his men. Singham tells Simmba that he is the officer, appointed by the committee to handle his case and gives a statement that Simmba killed Sadashiv and Gaurav in an act of self-defence. He also calls Dhurva's mother and wife, who each give a statement that it was Sadashiv and Gaurav who raped Aakruti and that the brothers ran a drug racket and several other criminal activities. Singham reveals that he helped Simmba despite being against his corrupt actions, so that he could instill a fear of law in the minds of men who do not respect women.\n\nAs Singham leaves Miramar Police Station, he is talking to DCP Veer Sooryavanshi<ref name=\"indtod\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/confirmed-akshay-kumar-will-romance-katrina-kaif-in-rohit-shetty-s-sooryavanshi-1507084-2019-04-22|title=Confirmed: Akshay Kumar will romance Katrina Kaif in Rohit Shetty's Sooryavanshi|website=India Today|access-date=22 April 2019|date=22 April 2019}}</ref> ([[Akshay Kumar]]). Singham congratulates him on his new post as ATS chief, and Sooryavanshi tells him that he will meet him soon.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Ranveer Singh]] as Inspector Sangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/marathi/movies/news/does-rohit-shetty-love-marathi/articleshow/64520631.cms|title=Does Rohit Shety love Marathi?|website=Times of india}}</ref>                \n*[[Sonu Sood]] as Durva Yashwanth Ranade                            \n*[[Sara Ali Khan]] as Shagun Sathe <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-new-pics-with-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-love-is-in-the-air-1962281|title=Simmba New Pics: With Ranveer Singh And Sara Ali Khan, Love Is In The Air|website=NDTV.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ashutosh Rana]] as Head Constable Nityanand Mohile\n* [[Siddhartha Jadhav]] as Santosh Tawade\n* Vaidehi Parshurami as Aakruti Dave\n* [[Ulka Gupta]] as Nandini Mohile\n* Suchita Bandekar as Mrs. Mohile\n* [[Sulbha Arya]] as Mrs. Iyer\n* [[Ashwini Kalsekar]] as Judge Smita Parulkar\n* [[Neha Mahajan]] as Kavya,Aakruti's friend\n* [[Nandu Madhav]] as Aakruti's father\n* [[Shri Swara Dubey]] as Varsha Ranade, Durva's wife\n* [[Sarita Joshi]] as Bharti Ranade, Durva's mother\n* Saurabh Gokhale as Gaurav Ranade (Giri), Durva's brother\n* Amrit Singh as Sadashiv Ranade (Sada),Durva's brother \n* Puja Agarwal as News Reporter\n* [[Vijay Patkar]] as Alok Borkar \n* Ashok Samartha as Lawyer Joshi\n* Ganesh Yadav as Lawyer Savalkar \n* [[Arun Nalawade]] as Vaman Rao\n* [[Uday Tikekar]] as Home Minister Vinayak Dutta\n* [[Vipin Sharma]] as Corporator David Cameron \n* Sahil Joshi as Chotu\n* Ravjeet Singh as Dheeraj, Shagun's friend\n* [[Ronjini Chakraborty]], as Poornima,Shagun's friend, works at the catering service\n* [[Anil Mange]] as Purab, a rickshaw driver obsessed with Poornima\n* [[Besant Ravi]] as Inspector Gaekwad\n* Sneha James as Inspector Gauri\n* Aarti Kulkarni as Good Food Lady \n* [[Ajay Devgn]] as DCP Bajirao Singham (Extended Cameo)\n* [[Akshay Kumar]] as DCP Veer Sooryavanshi (cameo appearance)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/akshay-kumar-to-have-a-special-cameo-in-rohit-shettys-simmba-starring-ranveer-singh/articleshow/67272892.cms|title=Akshay Kumar to have a special cameo appearance in Rohit Shetty's 'Simmba' starring Ranveer Singh - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n* [[Tusshar Kapoor]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Kunal Khemu]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Shreyas Talpade]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Arshad Warsi]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\" (the song is from his film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'')\n* [[Karan Johar]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Sudha Chandran]] (Cameo)\n* Sayli Patil as daughter of Home minister Vinayak Dutta\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nIt is a remake of the [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language film ''[[Temper (film)|Temper]]'' (2015). Shetty said, \"We wanted to take four-five scenes from Temper but... thought it's better to buy the rights\".<ref name=\"announced\"/> The film has an estimated production budget of {{INRConvert|80|c|link=yes}}.<ref name=\"budget\"/>\nPrincipal photography for ''Simmba'' began in June 2018.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/simmba-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-film/Simmba-Ranveer-Singh-and-Sara-Ali-Khan-to-begin-shooting-their-first-schedule-set-in-Hyderabad/photostory/64456441.cms |title='Simmba': Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan to begin shooting their first schedule set in Hyderabad \u2013 'Simmba': All you need to know about the Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan film |website=The Times of India |access-date=24 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618050026/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/simmba-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-film/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-begin-shooting-their-first-schedule-set-in-hyderabad/photostory/64456441.cms |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  It was mainly filmed in [[Goa]] and [[Kolhapur]], with some filming in [[Hyderabad]] and extra sequences filmed at [[Mehboob Studio]]s in [[Mumbai]].<ref name=\"reception\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/291118/ranveer-singh-to-shoot-for-simmba-after-his-reception.html|title=Ranveer Singh to shoot for Simmba after his reception|last=Varma|first=Lipika|date=29 November 2018|website=Deccan Chronicle|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204195753/https://deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/291118/ranveer-singh-to-shoot-for-simmba-after-his-reception.html|archive-date=4 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 June 2018, the crew filmed the song, \"Simmba Aala Re Aala Simmba Aala\", at [[Ramoji Film City]] in Hyderabad.  On Instagram, Singh noted the large scale of the production and said that it was the biggest song of his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/video/simmba-ranveer-singh-ecstatic-he-shoots-his-biggest-song-simmba-aala-re-417729|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh is ecstatic as he shoots for his biggest song Simmba Aala Re|website=PINKVILLA|access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegal issues surrounding the production of Khan's debut-film [[Kedarnath (film)|''Kedarnath'']] interfered with the production of ''Simmba''. Khan was scheduled to shoot for both films around the same time. A lawsuit shut down the production of ''Kedarnath'' and Khan allotted the time to work on ''Simmba''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/kedarnath-kriarj-entertainment-executive-alleges-abhishek-kapoor-made-unreasonable-demands-during-shoot-4348713.html|title=Kedarnath: KriArj Entertainment executive alleges Abhishek Kapoor made unreasonable demands during shoot|date=13 February 2018|publisher=FirstPost|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816142127/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/kedarnath-kriarj-entertainment-executive-alleges-abhishek-kapoor-made-unreasonable-demands-during-shoot-4348713.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kedarnath-makers-kriarj-entertainment-take-their-tussle-with-director-abhishek-kapoor-to-court-4352859.html|title=Kedarnath makers KriArj Entertainment take their tussle with director Abhishek Kapoor to court|date=15 February 2018|publisher=FirstPost|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619170124/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kedarnath-makers-kriarj-entertainment-take-their-tussle-with-director-abhishek-kapoor-to-court-4352859.html|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Kedarnath's'' director, [[Abhishek Kapoor]], sued Khan because his film would be delayed and it would no longer mark the debut of Khan. The two settled out of court when Khan agreed to split her time between both films.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/reel/902831/some-stories-choose-you-and-kedarnath-was-one-of-them-abhishek-kapoor-on-the-films-journey|title='Some stories choose you and Kedarnath was one of them': Abhishek Kapoor on the film's journey|last=Raman|first=Sruthi Ganapathy|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102339/https://scroll.in/reel/902831/some-stories-choose-you-and-kedarnath-was-one-of-them-abhishek-kapoor-on-the-films-journey|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n<!-- Left in here in case anyone wants to incorporate additional information into this section.\nCertain legal issues regarding the production of Sara Ali Khan's first film [[Kedarnath (film)|''Kedarnath'']] interfered with ''Simmba's'' production (as she was to shoot for both films around the same time) and caused some confusion for the parties involved. In February 2018, a dispute between ''Kedarnath'' director [[Abhishek Kapoor]] and its producers [[KriArj Entertainment]] led to a lawsuit that threatened the completion of its production. Due to having free days as per the ''Kedarnath'' court case, Khan allotted those days to film with the ''Simmba'' crew; this decision was unfitting to Kapoor, who took Khan to court.  The case also had an effect on the release of the ''Kedarnath''; as the producers ended up losing several lucrative prospective release slots near the end of the year; it seemed as if the film would be releasing in 2019 and that ''Simmba'' would be instead Sara Ali Khan's debut film.  Several media outlets speculated and even reported as such.  However, when the producers' of Ajay Devgn-starrer ''[[Total Dhamaal]]'' relinquished their 7 December release date in favour of late February 2019, RSVP Movies was quick to secure it for ''Kedarnath.''<ref name=\"timesnownews.com2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/kedarnath-dialogue-promo-unabashed-sara-ali-khan-asks-for-sushant-singh-rajput-s-attention/325692|title=Kedarnath dialogue promo: Unabashed Sara Ali Khan asks for Sushant Singh Rajput\u2019s attention {{!}} Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=6 December 2018}}</ref> This allowed Khan to debut with it and keep ''Simmba'' as her second film, as was originally planned.-->\n\nIn October 2018, lead actors Singh and Khan left for Switzerland to film a song sequence for the film.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/photos/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-head-switzerland-428723|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan head to Switzerland|website=PINKVILLA|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121246/https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/photos/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-head-switzerland-428723|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By late October, the crew had returned to Mumbai to film a second song, \"Aankh Marey\"\u2014a remake of a 90s classic song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latestly.com/entertainment/sara-ali-khan-and-ranveer-singh-shoot-a-dance-number-for-simmba-view-pics-461510.html|title=Sara Ali Khan and Ranveer Singh Shoot a Dance Number for Simmba \u2013 View Pics|date= 30 October 2018|website=Latestly|access-date= 9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause Singh was to be married in November 2018, Shetty shot most of the major sequences before the wedding date. Only the final sequence was left to be filmed after the wedding.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/its-a-wrap-for-ranveer-singh-starrer-simmba/articleshow/66971594.cms|title=It's a wrap for Ranveer Singh-starrer 'Simmba' - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208041551/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/its-a-wrap-for-ranveer-singh-starrer-simmba/articleshow/66971594.cms|archive-date=8 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A double for Singh was used to complete patch work of a [[dhaba]] fight scene in Goa; various camera angles were used so that the double would resemble Singh.<ref name=\"reception\"/>\n\nThe film wrapped shooting in early December 2018.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Simmba\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George-DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 27 December 2018\n| recorded     = 2018\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature Film Soundtrack]]\n| length       = 23:05\n| label        = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| language     = [[Hindi]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|YvOzvPxO49U|Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Tanishk Bagchi]]\n| type = soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Zero (2018 film)|Zero]]\n| prev_year = 2018\n| title = Simmba\n| year = 2018\n| next_title = [[Fraud Saiyaan]]\n| next_year = 2019}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = Lijo George & DJ Chetas\n| type = soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Loveyatri]]\n| prev_year = 2018\n| title = Simmba\n| year = 2018\n| next_title = [[Good Newwz]]\n| next_year = 2019}}\n{{Extra chronology \n| artist= [[S. Thaman]]\n| type= soundtrack \n| prev_title= [[Mr. Majnu]]\n| prev_year= 2018\n| title= Simmba\n| year= 2018\n| next_title= [[Ninu Veedani Needanu Nene]]\n| next_year= 2019\n}}\n}}\n\nThe songs are composed by [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George-DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]] while the lyrics are written by [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]], [[Rashmi Virag]], [[Kumaar]] and [[Kunaal Verma]]. The soundtrack album was released on 27 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/simmba/h,1tom,r4ZA_|title=Simmba - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|publisher=[[Saavn]]}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" is a remake of the song \"Aankh Maare\" from the 1996 film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'', originally composed by [[Viju Shah]] and written by [[Anand Bakshi]], sung by [[Kumar Sanu]] and [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], and picturised on [[Arshad Warsi]] and [[Simran (actress)|Simran]]; Warsi makes a cameo appearance in the ''Simmba'' version's music video, with Sanu's voice. The song was remade for the film, with the music reproduced by Tanishk Bagchi, S. Thaman  and Chandan Saxena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/simmba-aankh-marey-song-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-burn-the-dance-floor/20061169|title=Simmba Aankh Marey Song: Ranveer Singh And Sara Ali Khan Burn The Dance Floor|website=Mid-day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206125108/https://www.mid-day.com/articles/simmba-aankh-marey-song-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-burn-the-dance-floor/20061169|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live|date=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-recreate-ladka-aankh-maare-for-simmba/articleshow/64739456.cms|title=Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan. Tanishq Bagchi recreate \"Ladka Aankh Maare\" for Simmba|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=22 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823014310/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-recreate-ladka-aankh-maare-for-simmba/articleshow/64739456.cms|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The song \"Tere Bin\" is a recreation of [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]]'s 1996 [[qawwali]] song \"Tere Bin Nahin Lagda\". The remake is sung by his nephew [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]] with [[Asees Kaur]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Simmba song Tere Bin: Check out the recreated version of the classic Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan track ft. Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan |url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-tere-bin-check-out-the-recreated-version-of-the-classic-nusrat-fateh-ali-khan-track-ft-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-bollywood-news/330881 |agency=[[Times Now]] |date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Track listing\n| total_length = 23:05\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = [[Aankh Maarey]]\n| extra1 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Kumar Sanu]]\n| music1 = [[Tanishk Bagchi]]\n| lyrics1 = [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]]\n| length1 = 03:33\n| title2 = Tere Bin\n| extra2 = [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Asees Kaur]], Tanishk Bagchi\n| lyrics2 = [[Rashmi Virag]]\n| music2 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| length2 = 03:51\n| title3 = Aala Re Aala\n| extra3 = [[Dev Negi]], [[Goldie]]\n| lyrics3 = Shabbir Ahmed\n| length3 = 03:20\n| music3 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| title4 = Mera Wala Dance\n| extra4 = [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Nakash Aziz]]\n| lyrics4 = [[Kumaar]], [[Kunaal Verma]]\n| length4 = 03:20\n| music4 = Lijo George-DJ Chetas\n| title5 = Bandeya Re Bandeya\n| length5 = 04:15\n| extra5 = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Asees Kaur]]\n| music5 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| lyrics5 = Rashmi Virag\n| title6 = Simmba\n| extra6 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| music6 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| length6 = 02:06\n| title7 = Simmba\n| extra7 = [[S. Thaman]]\n| music7 = S.Thaman\n| length7 = 02:40\n| all_writing = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| note6 = Theme 1\n| note7 = Theme 2\n}}\n\n== Marketing and release ==\n\n[[File:Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan promote \u2018Simmba\u2019 at 98.3 FM Radio Mirchi.jpg|thumb|[[Ranveer Singh]] and [[Sara Ali Khan]] promoting the film in 2018]]\n\n''Simmba'' was released in countries of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] on 27 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-movie-meta-review-uae-ranveer-singh-starrer-is-predictable-but-entertaining-say-critic/337748|title=Simmba movie meta review UAE: Ranveer Singh starrer is predictable but entertaining, say critics - Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref> It was released in India and other countries on 28 December.<ref name=\"announced\"/> It was shown on 4020 screens in India and 963 screens overseas, for a worldwide screen total of 4983 screens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeebiz.com/india/news-simmba-box-office-collection-day-1-ranveer-singh-ajay-devgn-and-sara-ali-khan-film-set-for-rs-25-crore-opening-blockbuster-movie-reviews-taran-adarsh-77876|title=Simmba Box Office Collection day 1: Trade analyst made this big prediction for Ranveer Singh film|date=28 December 2018|website=Zee Business|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2018, the producers announced the start of principal photography with a skit video featuring actors Singh and Khan, director Shetty, and producer Johar.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-ranveer-singh-sara-ali-khan-are-all-set-glimpses-of-day-1-1863501|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh, Sara Ali Khan Are All Set. Glimpses Of Day 1|work=NDTV.com|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004000813/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-ranveer-singh-sara-ali-khan-are-all-set-glimpses-of-day-1-1863501|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2018, the producers released a new poster on Twitter, featuring Ranveer Singh's Bhalerao silhouetted in front of a police uniform, to announce the release of the film's trailer on 3 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/make-way-for-the-dynamite-countdown-for-ranveer-singhs-simmba-trailer-begins-check-out-the-new-poster/324019|title=Make way for the dynamite: Countdown for Ranveer Singh's Simmba trailer begins - check out the new poster Bollywood News|access-date=3 December 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203104100/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/make-way-for-the-dynamite-countdown-for-ranveer-singhs-simmba-trailer-begins-check-out-the-new-poster/324019|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  On 2 December, a second poster was released, depicting a uniformed and gun-wielding Bhalerao.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-trailer-ranveer-singh/story-bDVAaUBbDDUJS8p4bjQPhK.html|title=Before Simmba trailer, here are all the posters of Ranveer Singh film|date=3 December 2018|website=hindustan times|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203135350/https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-trailer-ranveer-singh/story-bDVAaUBbDDUJS8p4bjQPhK.html|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  On 3 December, the official trailer was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-trailer-get-ready-for-a-ranveer-singh-explosion-as-rohit-shettys-all-set-to-end-the-year-with-a-blast-bollywood-news/324247|title=Simmba trailer: Get ready for a Ranveer Singh explosion as Rohit Shetty's all set to end the year with a blast Bollywood News|access-date=3 December 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203152128/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-trailer-get-ready-for-a-ranveer-singh-explosion-as-rohit-shettys-all-set-to-end-the-year-with-a-blast-bollywood-news/324247|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 December 2018, the first song from the film was released, titled \"Aankh Marey,\" a remake of the original song from the 1996 hit film [[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|''Tere Mere Sapne''.]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-aankh-marey-releases-today-on-december-6-heres-why-this-date-has-a-special-significance-bollywood-news/326754|title=Simmba song Aankh Marey releases today on December 6 - here's why this date has a special significance Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102550/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-aankh-marey-releases-today-on-december-6-heres-why-this-date-has-a-special-significance-bollywood-news/326754|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  It is sung by [[Kumar Sanu]] (who also sung the original with [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]]), [[Mika Singh]], and [[Neha Kakkar]].  Actor [[Arshad Warsi]], whose film and song debut was with the original, appeared again in the video for the ''Simmba'' remake, along with several actors from another film from director Rohit Shetty, ''[[Golmaal]]'': [[Kunal Khemu]], [[Shreyas Talpade]], and [[Tusshar Kapoor]]. The release date for the remake was specifically chosen to coincide with the release date of the original 22 years earlier (6 December 1996).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 6 December 2017, Singh and the film's producers tweeted a poster of Singh as uniformed Inspector Sangram Bhalerao, wearing sunglasses and standing in an open-mouthed pose.<ref name=\"announced\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-poster-ranveer-singh-plays-a-quirky-cop-in-first-film-with-rohit-shetty/story-N3NkQhYb8wVrO8MxNNVm0K.html|title=Simmba first look: Ranveer Singh, Rohit Shetty film reminds you of Ram Lakhan, Singham|date=7 December 2017|website=hindustan times|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203202706/https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-poster-ranveer-singh-plays-a-quirky-cop-in-first-film-with-rohit-shetty/story-N3NkQhYb8wVrO8MxNNVm0K.html|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"promotions\">{{Cite news|last1=Shinde|first1=Prajwal|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/opinion/the-informer/dance-revolution/articleshow/65941133.cms|title=Simmba Cast at Kris Gethin Gym Chembur|date=2 March 2019|work=Mumbai Mirror|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''Simmba'' released to \"mixed to positive\" reviews from critics.<ref name=\":5\" /> Ambica Schin of ''[[Khaleej Times]]'' gave the film four stars out of five and sums up, \"If you are on the lookout for a totally masala, paisa vasool movie to end the year with a bang, we recommend you watch ''Simmba''. The melodramatic, over-the-top film is sure to leave you on a high\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.khaleejtimes.com/citytimes/bollywood/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-dominates-in-this-masala-flick-|title='Simmba' movie review: Ranveer dominates in this masala flick|website= Khaleej Times |first=Ambica|last=Sachin|date=27 December 2018|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> [[Taran Adarsh]] of [[Bollywood Hungama]] declared it a \"winner\" with four stars out of five, writing, \"Rohit borrows the essence from ''Temper'', but modifies a major chunk of that film... What eventually unfolds on screen is so different, in a positive way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/critic-review/|title=Simmba Movie Review|date=28 December 2018|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]}}</ref> Anwesha Madhukalya of ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]'' wrote, \"It is indeed time to rejoice for the young star's fans for Simmba has announced the arrival of Ranveer Singh in the big league\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/trending/entertainment/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singh-shines-in-this-repackaging-of-an-80s-movie/story/304947.html|title=Simmba Movie Review: Ranveer Singh shines in this repackaging of an 80s movie|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Times of India]]'', Ronak Kotecha rated it three and a half stars out of five, terming the film as \"a potboiler that you expect it to be, where the good surely outweighs the bad\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/simmba/movie-review/67276511.cms|title=SIMMBA MOVIE REVIEW|first=Ronak|last=Kotecha|website=Times of India|date=27 December 2018|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Suparno Sarkar of ''[[International Business Times]]'' also gave it three and a half stars out of five, writing, \"''Simmba'' is a complete masala entertainer that is loaded with good dialogues, humour, heart-felt emotion and high-octane action. It lacks logic at various levels, but never ceases to entertain\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/simmba-movie-review-typical-rohit-shetty-film-never-ceases-entertain-788898|title=Simmba movie review: Typical Rohit Shetty film but never ceases to entertain|first=Suparno|last=Sarkar|date=28 December 2018|website=International Business Times, India Edition}}</ref> A critic for ''[[The Economic Times]]'' agreed, also rating it three and a half stars out of five, but felt that \"[t]he film takes a preachy turn in the second half and the narrative gets predictable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/simmba-review-ranveer-singh-makes-it-worth-the-watch/articleshow/67318096.cms|title='Simmba' review: Ranveer Singh makes it worth the watch|date=31 December 2018|publisher=|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', [[Raja Sen]] rated the film three stars out of five, writing, \"[A]s it stands, ''Simmba'' is not only ahead of ''Singham'', but far superior to ''[[Dabangg]]'', the blockbuster that defines the genre\". He appreciated Singh for the energy he brought to the role, but found Khan was restricted by her role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singh-lifts-this-rohit-shetty-blockbuster/story-CbMRThX8I9dJ1hLMmu2vAJ.html|title=Simmba movie review: Ranveer Singh and Rohit Shetty create an angry cop movie universe|date=28 December 2018|website=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave the film two and a half stars out of five, finding the first half to be \"a sporadically enjoyable comedy\", but found the second half to be \"less enjoying\": \"The film leaves a lot to be desired, but a star is re-born\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/simmba-movie-review-rohit-shetty-film-leaves-a-lot-to-be-desired-but-a-star-is-re-born-1986835.html|title=Simmba Movie Review: Rohit Shetty Film Leaves a Lot to be Desired, But a Star is Re-born|website=News18}}</ref> Uday Bhatia of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' concurred with Masand: but credited Singh for playing his \"cardboard creation\" of a character with an \"underlying sweetness that renders it more winsome than the humourless masculinity of Devgan's Singham\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/ICrn1m7VU6y6Zv7kezOgJL/Simmba-movie-review-Crash-and-Burn.html|title='Simmba' movie review: Crash and Burn|last=Bhatia|first=Uday|date=28 December 2018|website=Live mint|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe box office collection figures for opening weekend of the film as presented on Bollywood Hungama are: First day It earned {{INR|link=yes}}20.72 crore nett in India which made it Singh's highest-opening film as of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-box-office-collection-day-1-film-emerges-as-ranveer-singhs-highest-opener-till-date-earns-ove-1969784|title=Simmba Box Office Collection Day 1: Film Emerges As Ranveer Singh's Highest Opener Till Date, Earns Over Rs 20 Crore|website=NDTV.com|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref> On second day it collected {{INR}}23.33 crore nett and {{INR}}31.06 crore on third day. Total first weekend nett domestic collection was {{INR}}75.11 crore. The opening week pan-India collection was {{INR}} 150.81 crore, which made it a hit film.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=taran_adarsh|author=Taran Adarsh|date=4 January 2019|number=1081099833778233345|title=#Simmba roars and scores at the BO... Crosses \u20b9 150 cr mark in Week 1... Glowing word of mouth has converted into footfalls... Fri 20.72 cr, Sat 23.33 cr, Sun 31.06 cr, Mon 21.24 cr, Tue 28.19 cr, Wed 14.49 cr, Thu 11.78 cr. Total: \u20b9 150.81 cr. India biz. SUPER HIT.r]}}</ref>\n\nIn its second week on eighth day domestic collection was {{INR}}9.02 crore. On ninth day collection rose to {{INR}}13.32 crore. Tenth day collection is {{INR}}17.49 crore. Eleventh day collection is {{INR}}6.16. Twelfth day collection is {{INR}}6.03. Thirteen day collection is {{INR}}5.31 and ending at 4.29 crore, taking second week collection to {{INR}}61.62 crore. The domestic gross is {{INR}}308.09 crore. It becomes [[Rohit Shetty]]'s biggest hit as it beats lifetime business of [[Chennai Express]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-is-rohit-shetty-s-biggest-hit-ranveer-singh-film-beats-lifetime-business-of-chennai-express-here-are-10-records-it-broke/story-lEl9QUM5KuAKdnjqixW6dP_amp.html|title= Simmba is Rohit Shetty's biggest hit, Ranveer Singh film beats lifetime business of Chennai Express.|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed {{INRConvert|92.10|c}} from overseas markets as estimated by [[Bollywood Hungama]]. The gross worldwide is {{INRconvert|400.19|c}}.<ref name=box1/> [[List of Bollywood films of 2018|It became third highest-grossing film of 2018]].\n\nIn 23 days of its release the domestic gross of the film touched the {{INR}}300 crore mark. It took 40 days for the film to gross {{INR}}350 crore worldwide.<ref name=box1/>\n\nIn Pakistan, the film has collected more than {{PKR|19 crore}} till its fifth weekend.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.entertainmentpk.com/simmba-hits-20-crore-mark-at-pakistans-box-office/|title=SIMMBA NEARING THE 20 CRORE MARK AT PAKISTAN'S BOX OFFICE!|date=29 January 2019|accessdate=29 January 2019|website=EntertainmentPK.com|author=Ali Zain}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|tt7212726}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|simmba}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/ Simmba] on [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n* [https://masanlyrics.com/tere-bin-nahi-lagda-dil-mera-dholna-lyrics/ Tere bin nahi lagda Lyrics Simmba]\n\n{{Rohit Shetty}}\n{{Dharma Productions}}\n{{Singham}}\n\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rohit Shetty]]\n[[Category:Cop Universe]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Telstra People's Choice Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Film spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Indian rape and revenge films]]\n[[Category:Indian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films set in Goa]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Maharashtra Police]]\n[[Category:Reliance Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape in India]]\n[[Category:Indian police films]]\n[[Category:Hindi remakes of Telugu films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 Indian Hindi-language action film directed by Rohit Shetty}}\n{{distinguish|Simba}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Simmba\n| image          = Simmba poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Rohit Shetty]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n*Rohit Shetty\n*Hiroo Yash Johar\n*[[Karan Johar]]\n*Apoorva Mehta<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/simmba-team-gets-goofy-on-the-sets/articleshow/64707897.cms |title='Simmba' team gets goofy on the sets |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926142157/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/simmba-team-gets-goofy-on-the-sets/articleshow/64707897.cms |archive-date=26 September 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay     = Yunus Sajawal<br>[[Sajid-Farhad|Sajid Samji]]\n| writer         = [[Farhad Samji]]<br>'''Dialogues:'''\n| story          = [[Rohit Shetty]]<br>[[Vakkantham Vamsi]]\n| narrator       = [[Ajay Devgn]]\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Ranveer Singh]]|[[Sonu Sood]]|[[Sara Ali Khan]]|[[Ashutosh Rana]]|[[Siddhartha Jadhav]]}}\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Tanishk Bagchi]]<br />Lijo George \u2013 DJ Chetas<br />[[S. Thaman]]<br />'''Score:'''<br />[[Amar Mohile]]<br />Chandan Saxena<br />[[S. Thaman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jomon T. John]]\n| editing        = Bunty Negi\n| studio         = [[Reliance Entertainment]]<br />[[Dharma Productions]]<br /> Rohit Shetty Picturez\n| distributor    = [[Reliance Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2018|12|27|[[United Arab Emirates]]|2018|12|28|[[India]]}}\n| runtime        = 159 minutes<ref name=\"bbfc\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/simmba-2018|title=Simmba {{!}} British Board of Film Classification|website=www.bbfc.co.uk|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n| budget         = {{INR|80\u2013139 [[crore]]|link=yes}}<ref name=\"budget\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.zeebiz.com/india/news-simmba-box-office-collection-prediction-day-1-ranveer-singh-ajay-devgn-rohit-shetty-crossover-film-to-earn-rs-20-crore-analyst-says-77757 |title=Simmba Box Office Collection Prediction: Ranveer Singh, Ajay Devgn set to wow you! Rohit Shetty crossover film set to bag big amount |date=27 December 2018 |website=[[Zee Business]] |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=5568 |title=Simmba \u2013 Movie \u2013 Box Office India |website=Box Office India |access-date=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{estimation}} {{INR}}400.19 crore<ref name=\"box1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office |title=Simmba Box Office Collection till Now |website=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singhs-pizzazz-is-lost-to-a-cliched-womens-rights-saga-that-sidelines-women-5804601.html |title=Simmba movie review: Ranveer Singh's pizzazz is lost to a clich\u00e9d women's rights saga that sidelines women |last=Vetticad |first=Anna MM |date=28 December 2018 |work=[[Firstpost]] |access-date=1 April 2019 |publisher=[[Network 18]] |author-link=Anna M. M. Vetticad}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Simmba''''' is a 2018 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[action film]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=simmba.htm |title=Simmba (2018) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref> directed by [[Rohit Shetty]] and written by Yunus Sajawal and [[Sajid-Farhad]]. The third installment of [[Shetty's Police Universe]], the film was produced by Shetty under his banner Rohit Shetty Picturez and [[Karan Johar]], Hiroo Yash Johar and Apoorva Mehta via [[Dharma Productions]]. [[Reliance Entertainment]] also co-produced and distributed the film. It stars [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Sonu Sood]] and [[Sara Ali Khan]], with [[Ajay Devgn]] reprising his role of Bajirao Singham in an extended cameo role. The film follows Sangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao, a corrupt police officer hailing from the same town as Singham, who is forced to lead a more righteous path after tragedy strikes those near him.\n\nThe film is an official partial remake of  the 2015 [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language film ''[[Temper (film)|Temper]]''.<ref name=\"announced\" /> [[Principal photography]] began in June 2018 with most scenes filmed in [[Goa]] and [[Kolhapur]]; the remaining \nwere shot at [[Hyderabad]] and [[Mehboob Studios]] in [[Mumbai]]. The shooting was wrapped up by early December in the same year. The film's soundtrack was composed by [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George \u2013 DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]], with lyrics written by [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]], [[Rashmi Virag]], [[Kumaar]] and [[Kunaal Verma]]. The soundtrack features remakes of two 1996 songs: \"Aankh Marey\" originally from the film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'', and the [[qawwali]] song \"Tere Bin\" by [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]].\n\n''Simmba'' was released in countries of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] on 27 December 2018. The film was released in India and other international territories on the following day; it was distributed worldwide by [[Reliance Entertainment]]. The film received mixed reviews<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/box-office-update-ranveer-singh-fails-to-beat-ranbir-kapoor-as-the-opening-day-of-simmba-is-no-match-to-sanju/338830 |title=Box Office update: Ranveer Singh fails to beat Ranbir Kapoor as the opening day of Simmba is no match to that of Sanju's {{!}} Entertainment News |website=Times Now |access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>  from critics but became Singh's highest-earning opening film as of 2018 and went on to gross about {{INR|link=yes}}400 crore worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-box-office-day-3-ranveer-singh-breaks-personal-record-film-earns-rs-100-cr-worldwide/story-eo9EmtIgPO9xtXKcVZl9qK.html |title=Simmba box office day 3: Ranveer Singh breaks personal record, film earns Rs 100 cr worldwide |date=31 December 2018 |website=Hindustan Times |access-date=31 December 2018}}</ref> Later, it received the Australian [[Telstra People's Choice Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/india/english/life+and+trendz-epaper-lifntr/vijay+sethupathi+shah+rukh+khan+tabu+win+top+awards+at+iffm+awards+2019-newsid-129867114 |title=Vijay Sethupathi, Shah Rukh Khan, Tabu, win top awards at IFFM Awards 2019 - Life and Trendz &#124; DailyHunt |publisher=M.dailyhunt.in |date= |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao is an [[antihero]]ic orphan from Shivgadh, the same town where Bajirao Singham was raised. He observes how policemen make money in the form of bribes, finding himself motivated to become a police officer, and succeeds. Getting bribes from some local thieves and a jeweller, Simmba enjoys and takes full advantage of the lifestyle of a corrupt cop.\n\nHe is soon transferred to Miramar police station, where he sees Shagun Sathe and falls in love with her at first sight. He meets his fellow policemen and one of his juniors, Nityanand Mohile, who is an honest constable, hesitates to salute Simmba as he's a corrupt cop. To prove his worth in Miramar, he interrupts a pub party run by Durva Yashwant Ranade's brothers, Sadashiv \"Sada\" Ranade and Gaurav \"Giri\" Ranade and demands more money from them, whilst promising that he will let them continue with their illegal activities. Durva agrees and uses Simmba to free a land from an old person Vaaman Rao, who is forced to sign the papers by Simmba. Meanwhile, Simmba develops motherly and sisterly bonds with several women and girls, one of whom happens to be Aakruti Dave, a young woman who reminds Simmba of his teacher.\n\nAakruti files a complaint against Sada and Giri for dealing illicit drugs in their pub and using children as peddlers. Simmba initially ignores this after being pacified by Durva, and Shagun in the meantime falls in love with him. Meanwhile, Aakruti learns about the drug racket in the club and goes there one night with Chotu, a mute boy who's her student. She videotapes by cell phone to show evidence to the police, but is caught by Sada and Giri. Chotu discreetly records Sada and Giri assaulting Aakruti and flees once both of them realise.\n\nAakruti is brutally raped and murdered by Sada and Giri. Chotu tries to tell Akruti's friend Kavya about Akruti being in danger. Kavya whilst being chased by Durva's goons goes to Simmba to file Aakruti's missing complaint. Aakruti is found injured in hospital. Simmba tries to talk to her but she dies, leaving him devastated. Police recover the phone and the video and Durva sends his goons to get the phone from Simmba, who is present, mends his ways, and fights them all. Simmba finally wears his police uniform and seeing this change in him, Mohile finally salutes him as they arrest Sada and Giri. He apologises to Vaaman Rao, and returns the land swindled from him. In the court, Simmba is shocked to find Aakruti's video being deleted. He beats up Durva's friend who gave a false statement in the court, leading to his suspension orders. He decides to kill Sada and Giri before he goes, and plans to show it as an encounter. He shoots them both and shows as if he killed them in an act of self-defence. A SIT committee is set up by the state, who question Simmba's encounter. To achieve clarity to the situation, Home Minister Vinayak Dutta appoints a neutral officer to handle Aakruti's case, as well as Simmba's controversial encounter.\n\nEnraged, Durva and his goons capture Simmba. Suddenly DCP Bajirao Singham comes to his rescue and both of them beat up Durva and his men. Singham tells Simmba that he is the officer, appointed by the committee to handle his case and gives a statement that Simmba killed Sadashiv and Gaurav in an act of self-defence. He also calls Dhurva's mother and wife, who each give a statement that it was Sadashiv and Gaurav who raped Aakruti and that the brothers ran a drug racket and several other criminal activities. Singham reveals that he helped Simmba despite being against his corrupt actions, so that he could instill a fear of law in the minds of men who do not respect women.\n\nAs Singham leaves Miramar Police Station, he is talking to DCP Veer Sooryavanshi<ref name=\"indtod\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/confirmed-akshay-kumar-will-romance-katrina-kaif-in-rohit-shetty-s-sooryavanshi-1507084-2019-04-22|title=Confirmed: Akshay Kumar will romance Katrina Kaif in Rohit Shetty's Sooryavanshi|website=India Today|access-date=22 April 2019|date=22 April 2019}}</ref> ([[Akshay Kumar]]). Singham congratulates him on his new post as ATS chief, and Sooryavanshi tells him that he will meet him soon.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Ranveer Singh]] as Inspector Sangram \"Simmba\" Bhalerao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/marathi/movies/news/does-rohit-shetty-love-marathi/articleshow/64520631.cms|title=Does Rohit Shety love Marathi?|website=Times of india}}</ref>                \n*[[Sonu Sood]] as Durva Yashwanth Ranade                            \n*[[Sara Ali Khan]] as Shagun Sathe <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-new-pics-with-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-love-is-in-the-air-1962281|title=Simmba New Pics: With Ranveer Singh And Sara Ali Khan, Love Is In The Air|website=NDTV.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ashutosh Rana]] as Head Constable Nityanand Mohile\n* [[Siddhartha Jadhav]] as Santosh Tawade\n* Vaidehi Parshurami as Aakruti Dave\n* [[Ulka Gupta]] as Nandini Mohile\n* Suchita Bandekar as Mrs. Mohile\n* [[Sulbha Arya]] as Mrs. Iyer\n* [[Ashwini Kalsekar]] as Judge Smita Parulkar\n* [[Neha Mahajan]] as Kavya,Aakruti's friend\n* [[Nandu Madhav]] as Aakruti's father\n* [[Shri Swara Dubey]] as Varsha Ranade, Durva's wife\n* [[Sarita Joshi]] as Bharti Ranade, Durva's mother\n* Saurabh Gokhale as Gaurav Ranade (Giri), Durva's brother\n* Amrit Singh as Sadashiv Ranade (Sada),Durva's brother \n* Puja Agarwal as News Reporter\n* [[Vijay Patkar]] as Alok Borkar \n* Ashok Samartha as Lawyer Joshi\n* Ganesh Yadav as Lawyer Savalkar \n* [[Arun Nalawade]] as Vaman Rao\n* [[Uday Tikekar]] as Home Minister Vinayak Dutta\n* [[Vipin Sharma]] as Corporator David Cameron \n* Sahil Joshi as Chotu\n* Ravjeet Singh as Dheeraj, Shagun's friend\n* [[Ronjini Chakraborty]], as Poornima,Shagun's friend, works at the catering service\n* [[Anil Mange]] as Purab, a rickshaw driver obsessed with Poornima\n* [[Besant Ravi]] as Inspector Gaekwad\n* Sneha James as Inspector Gauri\n* Aarti Kulkarni as Good Food Lady \n* [[Ajay Devgn]] as DCP Bajirao Singham (Extended Cameo)\n* [[Akshay Kumar]] as DCP Veer Sooryavanshi (cameo appearance)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/akshay-kumar-to-have-a-special-cameo-in-rohit-shettys-simmba-starring-ranveer-singh/articleshow/67272892.cms|title=Akshay Kumar to have a special cameo appearance in Rohit Shetty's 'Simmba' starring Ranveer Singh - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n* [[Tusshar Kapoor]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Kunal Khemu]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Shreyas Talpade]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Arshad Warsi]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\" (the song is from his film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'')\n* [[Karan Johar]] in a cameo appearance in the song \"Aankh Marey\"\n* [[Sudha Chandran]] (Cameo)\n* Sayli Patil as daughter of Home minister Vinayak Dutta\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nIt is a remake of the [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language film ''[[Temper (film)|Temper]]'' (2015). Shetty said, \"We wanted to take four-five scenes from Temper but... thought it's better to buy the rights\".<ref name=\"announced\"/> The film has an estimated production budget of {{INRConvert|80|c|link=yes}}.<ref name=\"budget\"/>\nPrincipal photography for ''Simmba'' began in June 2018.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/simmba-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-film/Simmba-Ranveer-Singh-and-Sara-Ali-Khan-to-begin-shooting-their-first-schedule-set-in-Hyderabad/photostory/64456441.cms |title='Simmba': Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan to begin shooting their first schedule set in Hyderabad \u2013 'Simmba': All you need to know about the Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan film |website=The Times of India |access-date=24 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618050026/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/simmba-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-film/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-begin-shooting-their-first-schedule-set-in-hyderabad/photostory/64456441.cms |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  It was mainly filmed in [[Goa]] and [[Kolhapur]], with some filming in [[Hyderabad]] and extra sequences filmed at [[Mehboob Studio]]s in [[Mumbai]].<ref name=\"reception\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/291118/ranveer-singh-to-shoot-for-simmba-after-his-reception.html|title=Ranveer Singh to shoot for Simmba after his reception|last=Varma|first=Lipika|date=29 November 2018|website=Deccan Chronicle|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204195753/https://deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/291118/ranveer-singh-to-shoot-for-simmba-after-his-reception.html|archive-date=4 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 June 2018, the crew filmed the song, \"Simmba Aala Re Aala Simmba Aala\", at [[Ramoji Film City]] in Hyderabad.  On Instagram, Singh noted the large scale of the production and said that it was the biggest song of his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/video/simmba-ranveer-singh-ecstatic-he-shoots-his-biggest-song-simmba-aala-re-417729|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh is ecstatic as he shoots for his biggest song Simmba Aala Re|website=PINKVILLA|access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegal issues surrounding the production of Khan's debut-film [[Kedarnath (film)|''Kedarnath'']] interfered with the production of ''Simmba''. Khan was scheduled to shoot for both films around the same time. A lawsuit shut down the production of ''Kedarnath'' and Khan allotted the time to work on ''Simmba''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/kedarnath-kriarj-entertainment-executive-alleges-abhishek-kapoor-made-unreasonable-demands-during-shoot-4348713.html|title=Kedarnath: KriArj Entertainment executive alleges Abhishek Kapoor made unreasonable demands during shoot|date=13 February 2018|publisher=FirstPost|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816142127/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/kedarnath-kriarj-entertainment-executive-alleges-abhishek-kapoor-made-unreasonable-demands-during-shoot-4348713.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kedarnath-makers-kriarj-entertainment-take-their-tussle-with-director-abhishek-kapoor-to-court-4352859.html|title=Kedarnath makers KriArj Entertainment take their tussle with director Abhishek Kapoor to court|date=15 February 2018|publisher=FirstPost|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619170124/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kedarnath-makers-kriarj-entertainment-take-their-tussle-with-director-abhishek-kapoor-to-court-4352859.html|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Kedarnath's'' director, [[Abhishek Kapoor]], sued Khan because his film would be delayed and it would no longer mark the debut of Khan. The two settled out of court when Khan agreed to split her time between both films.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/reel/902831/some-stories-choose-you-and-kedarnath-was-one-of-them-abhishek-kapoor-on-the-films-journey|title='Some stories choose you and Kedarnath was one of them': Abhishek Kapoor on the film's journey|last=Raman|first=Sruthi Ganapathy|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102339/https://scroll.in/reel/902831/some-stories-choose-you-and-kedarnath-was-one-of-them-abhishek-kapoor-on-the-films-journey|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n<!-- Left in here in case anyone wants to incorporate additional information into this section.\nCertain legal issues regarding the production of Sara Ali Khan's first film [[Kedarnath (film)|''Kedarnath'']] interfered with ''Simmba's'' production (as she was to shoot for both films around the same time) and caused some confusion for the parties involved. In February 2018, a dispute between ''Kedarnath'' director [[Abhishek Kapoor]] and its producers [[KriArj Entertainment]] led to a lawsuit that threatened the completion of its production. Due to having free days as per the ''Kedarnath'' court case, Khan allotted those days to film with the ''Simmba'' crew; this decision was unfitting to Kapoor, who took Khan to court.  The case also had an effect on the release of the ''Kedarnath''; as the producers ended up losing several lucrative prospective release slots near the end of the year; it seemed as if the film would be releasing in 2019 and that ''Simmba'' would be instead Sara Ali Khan's debut film.  Several media outlets speculated and even reported as such.  However, when the producers' of Ajay Devgn-starrer ''[[Total Dhamaal]]'' relinquished their 7 December release date in favour of late February 2019, RSVP Movies was quick to secure it for ''Kedarnath.''<ref name=\"timesnownews.com2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/kedarnath-dialogue-promo-unabashed-sara-ali-khan-asks-for-sushant-singh-rajput-s-attention/325692|title=Kedarnath dialogue promo: Unabashed Sara Ali Khan asks for Sushant Singh Rajput\u2019s attention {{!}} Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=6 December 2018}}</ref> This allowed Khan to debut with it and keep ''Simmba'' as her second film, as was originally planned.-->\n\nIn October 2018, lead actors Singh and Khan left for Switzerland to film a song sequence for the film.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/photos/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-head-switzerland-428723|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan head to Switzerland|website=PINKVILLA|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121246/https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/photos/simmba-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-head-switzerland-428723|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By late October, the crew had returned to Mumbai to film a second song, \"Aankh Marey\"\u2014a remake of a 90s classic song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latestly.com/entertainment/sara-ali-khan-and-ranveer-singh-shoot-a-dance-number-for-simmba-view-pics-461510.html|title=Sara Ali Khan and Ranveer Singh Shoot a Dance Number for Simmba \u2013 View Pics|date= 30 October 2018|website=Latestly|access-date= 9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause Singh was to be married in November 2018, Shetty shot most of the major sequences before the wedding date. Only the final sequence was left to be filmed after the wedding.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/its-a-wrap-for-ranveer-singh-starrer-simmba/articleshow/66971594.cms|title=It's a wrap for Ranveer Singh-starrer 'Simmba' - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=9 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208041551/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/its-a-wrap-for-ranveer-singh-starrer-simmba/articleshow/66971594.cms|archive-date=8 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A double for Singh was used to complete patch work of a [[dhaba]] fight scene in Goa; various camera angles were used so that the double would resemble Singh.<ref name=\"reception\"/>\n\nThe film wrapped shooting in early December 2018.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Simmba\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George-DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 27 December 2018\n| recorded     = 2018\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature Film Soundtrack]]\n| length       = 23:05\n| label        = [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| language     = [[Hindi]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|YvOzvPxO49U|Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = [[Tanishk Bagchi]]\n| type = soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Zero (2018 film)|Zero]]\n| prev_year = 2018\n| title = Simmba\n| year = 2018\n| next_title = [[Fraud Saiyaan]]\n| next_year = 2019}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist = Lijo George & DJ Chetas\n| type = soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Loveyatri]]\n| prev_year = 2018\n| title = Simmba\n| year = 2018\n| next_title = [[Good Newwz]]\n| next_year = 2019}}\n{{Extra chronology \n| artist= [[S. Thaman]]\n| type= soundtrack \n| prev_title= [[Mr. Majnu]]\n| prev_year= 2018\n| title= Simmba\n| year= 2018\n| next_title= [[Ninu Veedani Needanu Nene]]\n| next_year= 2019\n}}\n}}\n\nThe songs are composed by [[Tanishk Bagchi]], Lijo George-DJ Chetas and [[S. Thaman]] while the lyrics are written by [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]], [[Rashmi Virag]], [[Kumaar]] and [[Kunaal Verma]]. The soundtrack album was released on 27 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/simmba/h,1tom,r4ZA_|title=Simmba - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|publisher=[[Saavn]]}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\" is a remake of the song \"Aankh Maare\" from the 1996 film ''[[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|Tere Mere Sapne]]'', originally composed by [[Viju Shah]] and written by [[Anand Bakshi]], sung by [[Kumar Sanu]] and [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]], and picturised on [[Arshad Warsi]] and [[Simran (actress)|Simran]]; Warsi makes a cameo appearance in the ''Simmba'' version's music video, with Sanu's voice. The song was remade for the film, with the music reproduced by Tanishk Bagchi, S. Thaman  and Chandan Saxena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/simmba-aankh-marey-song-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-burn-the-dance-floor/20061169|title=Simmba Aankh Marey Song: Ranveer Singh And Sara Ali Khan Burn The Dance Floor|website=Mid-day|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206125108/https://www.mid-day.com/articles/simmba-aankh-marey-song-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-burn-the-dance-floor/20061169|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live|date=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-recreate-ladka-aankh-maare-for-simmba/articleshow/64739456.cms|title=Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan. Tanishq Bagchi recreate \"Ladka Aankh Maare\" for Simmba|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=22 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823014310/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-to-recreate-ladka-aankh-maare-for-simmba/articleshow/64739456.cms|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The song \"Tere Bin\" is a recreation of [[Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]]'s 1996 [[qawwali]] song \"Tere Bin Nahin Lagda\". The remake is sung by his nephew [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]] with [[Asees Kaur]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Simmba song Tere Bin: Check out the recreated version of the classic Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan track ft. Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan |url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-tere-bin-check-out-the-recreated-version-of-the-classic-nusrat-fateh-ali-khan-track-ft-ranveer-singh-and-sara-ali-khan-bollywood-news/330881 |agency=[[Times Now]] |date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Track listing\n| total_length = 23:05\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = [[Aankh Maarey]]\n| extra1 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Kumar Sanu]]\n| music1 = [[Tanishk Bagchi]]\n| lyrics1 = [[Shabbir Ahmed (lyricist)|Shabbir Ahmed]]\n| length1 = 03:33\n| title2 = Tere Bin\n| extra2 = [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Asees Kaur]], Tanishk Bagchi\n| lyrics2 = [[Rashmi Virag]]\n| music2 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| length2 = 03:51\n| title3 = Aala Re Aala\n| extra3 = [[Dev Negi]], [[Goldie]]\n| lyrics3 = Shabbir Ahmed\n| length3 = 03:20\n| music3 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| title4 = Mera Wala Dance\n| extra4 = [[Neha Kakkar]], [[Nakash Aziz]]\n| lyrics4 = [[Kumaar]], [[Kunaal Verma]]\n| length4 = 03:20\n| music4 = Lijo George-DJ Chetas\n| title5 = Bandeya Re Bandeya\n| length5 = 04:15\n| extra5 = [[Arijit Singh]], [[Asees Kaur]]\n| music5 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| lyrics5 = Rashmi Virag\n| title6 = Simmba\n| extra6 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| music6 = Tanishk Bagchi\n| length6 = 02:06\n| title7 = Simmba\n| extra7 = [[S. Thaman]]\n| music7 = S.Thaman\n| length7 = 02:40\n| all_writing = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| note6 = Theme 1\n| note7 = Theme 2\n}}\n\n== Marketing and release ==\n\n[[File:Ranveer Singh and Sara Ali Khan promote \u2018Simmba\u2019 at 98.3 FM Radio Mirchi.jpg|thumb|[[Ranveer Singh]] and [[Sara Ali Khan]] promoting the film in 2018]]\n\n''Simmba'' was released in countries of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] on 27 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-movie-meta-review-uae-ranveer-singh-starrer-is-predictable-but-entertaining-say-critic/337748|title=Simmba movie meta review UAE: Ranveer Singh starrer is predictable but entertaining, say critics - Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref> It was released in India and other countries on 28 December.<ref name=\"announced\"/> It was shown on 4020 screens in India and 963 screens overseas, for a worldwide screen total of 4983 screens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeebiz.com/india/news-simmba-box-office-collection-day-1-ranveer-singh-ajay-devgn-and-sara-ali-khan-film-set-for-rs-25-crore-opening-blockbuster-movie-reviews-taran-adarsh-77876|title=Simmba Box Office Collection day 1: Trade analyst made this big prediction for Ranveer Singh film|date=28 December 2018|website=Zee Business|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2018, the producers announced the start of principal photography with a skit video featuring actors Singh and Khan, director Shetty, and producer Johar.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-ranveer-singh-sara-ali-khan-are-all-set-glimpses-of-day-1-1863501|title=Simmba: Ranveer Singh, Sara Ali Khan Are All Set. Glimpses Of Day 1|work=NDTV.com|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004000813/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-ranveer-singh-sara-ali-khan-are-all-set-glimpses-of-day-1-1863501|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2018, the producers released a new poster on Twitter, featuring Ranveer Singh's Bhalerao silhouetted in front of a police uniform, to announce the release of the film's trailer on 3 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/make-way-for-the-dynamite-countdown-for-ranveer-singhs-simmba-trailer-begins-check-out-the-new-poster/324019|title=Make way for the dynamite: Countdown for Ranveer Singh's Simmba trailer begins - check out the new poster Bollywood News|access-date=3 December 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203104100/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/make-way-for-the-dynamite-countdown-for-ranveer-singhs-simmba-trailer-begins-check-out-the-new-poster/324019|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  On 2 December, a second poster was released, depicting a uniformed and gun-wielding Bhalerao.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-trailer-ranveer-singh/story-bDVAaUBbDDUJS8p4bjQPhK.html|title=Before Simmba trailer, here are all the posters of Ranveer Singh film|date=3 December 2018|website=hindustan times|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203135350/https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-trailer-ranveer-singh/story-bDVAaUBbDDUJS8p4bjQPhK.html|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  On 3 December, the official trailer was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-trailer-get-ready-for-a-ranveer-singh-explosion-as-rohit-shettys-all-set-to-end-the-year-with-a-blast-bollywood-news/324247|title=Simmba trailer: Get ready for a Ranveer Singh explosion as Rohit Shetty's all set to end the year with a blast Bollywood News|access-date=3 December 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203152128/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-trailer-get-ready-for-a-ranveer-singh-explosion-as-rohit-shettys-all-set-to-end-the-year-with-a-blast-bollywood-news/324247|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 December 2018, the first song from the film was released, titled \"Aankh Marey,\" a remake of the original song from the 1996 hit film [[Tere Mere Sapne (1996 film)|''Tere Mere Sapne''.]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-aankh-marey-releases-today-on-december-6-heres-why-this-date-has-a-special-significance-bollywood-news/326754|title=Simmba song Aankh Marey releases today on December 6 - here's why this date has a special significance Bollywood News|website=www.timesnownews.com|language=en-GB|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206102550/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/simmba-song-aankh-marey-releases-today-on-december-6-heres-why-this-date-has-a-special-significance-bollywood-news/326754|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  It is sung by [[Kumar Sanu]] (who also sung the original with [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]]), [[Mika Singh]], and [[Neha Kakkar]].  Actor [[Arshad Warsi]], whose film and song debut was with the original, appeared again in the video for the ''Simmba'' remake, along with several actors from another film from director Rohit Shetty, ''[[Golmaal]]'': [[Kunal Khemu]], [[Shreyas Talpade]], and [[Tusshar Kapoor]]. The release date for the remake was specifically chosen to coincide with the release date of the original 22 years earlier (6 December 1996).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 6 December 2017, Singh and the film's producers tweeted a poster of Singh as uniformed Inspector Sangram Bhalerao, wearing sunglasses and standing in an open-mouthed pose.<ref name=\"announced\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-poster-ranveer-singh-plays-a-quirky-cop-in-first-film-with-rohit-shetty/story-N3NkQhYb8wVrO8MxNNVm0K.html|title=Simmba first look: Ranveer Singh, Rohit Shetty film reminds you of Ram Lakhan, Singham|date=7 December 2017|website=hindustan times|access-date=3 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203202706/https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-poster-ranveer-singh-plays-a-quirky-cop-in-first-film-with-rohit-shetty/story-N3NkQhYb8wVrO8MxNNVm0K.html|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"promotions\">{{Cite news|last1=Shinde|first1=Prajwal|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/opinion/the-informer/dance-revolution/articleshow/65941133.cms|title=Simmba Cast at Kris Gethin Gym Chembur|date=2 March 2019|work=Mumbai Mirror|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''Simmba'' released to \"mixed to positive\" reviews from critics.<ref name=\":5\" /> Ambica Schin of ''[[Khaleej Times]]'' gave the film four stars out of five and sums up, \"If you are on the lookout for a totally masala, paisa vasool movie to end the year with a bang, we recommend you watch ''Simmba''. The melodramatic, over-the-top film is sure to leave you on a high\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.khaleejtimes.com/citytimes/bollywood/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-dominates-in-this-masala-flick-|title='Simmba' movie review: Ranveer dominates in this masala flick|website= Khaleej Times |first=Ambica|last=Sachin|date=27 December 2018|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> [[Taran Adarsh]] of [[Bollywood Hungama]] declared it a \"winner\" with four stars out of five, writing, \"Rohit borrows the essence from ''Temper'', but modifies a major chunk of that film... What eventually unfolds on screen is so different, in a positive way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/critic-review/|title=Simmba Movie Review|date=28 December 2018|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]}}</ref> Anwesha Madhukalya of ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]'' wrote, \"It is indeed time to rejoice for the young star's fans for Simmba has announced the arrival of Ranveer Singh in the big league\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/trending/entertainment/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singh-shines-in-this-repackaging-of-an-80s-movie/story/304947.html|title=Simmba Movie Review: Ranveer Singh shines in this repackaging of an 80s movie|website=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Times of India]]'', Ronak Kotecha rated it three and a half stars out of five, terming the film as \"a potboiler that you expect it to be, where the good surely outweighs the bad\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/simmba/movie-review/67276511.cms|title=SIMMBA MOVIE REVIEW|first=Ronak|last=Kotecha|website=Times of India|date=27 December 2018|access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Suparno Sarkar of ''[[International Business Times]]'' also gave it three and a half stars out of five, writing, \"''Simmba'' is a complete masala entertainer that is loaded with good dialogues, humour, heart-felt emotion and high-octane action. It lacks logic at various levels, but never ceases to entertain\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/simmba-movie-review-typical-rohit-shetty-film-never-ceases-entertain-788898|title=Simmba movie review: Typical Rohit Shetty film but never ceases to entertain|first=Suparno|last=Sarkar|date=28 December 2018|website=International Business Times, India Edition}}</ref> A critic for ''[[The Economic Times]]'' agreed, also rating it three and a half stars out of five, but felt that \"[t]he film takes a preachy turn in the second half and the narrative gets predictable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/simmba-review-ranveer-singh-makes-it-worth-the-watch/articleshow/67318096.cms|title='Simmba' review: Ranveer Singh makes it worth the watch|date=31 December 2018|publisher=|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', [[Raja Sen]] rated the film three stars out of five, writing, \"[A]s it stands, ''Simmba'' is not only ahead of ''Singham'', but far superior to ''[[Dabangg]]'', the blockbuster that defines the genre\". He appreciated Singh for the energy he brought to the role, but found Khan was restricted by her role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-movie-review-ranveer-singh-lifts-this-rohit-shetty-blockbuster/story-CbMRThX8I9dJ1hLMmu2vAJ.html|title=Simmba movie review: Ranveer Singh and Rohit Shetty create an angry cop movie universe|date=28 December 2018|website=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave the film two and a half stars out of five, finding the first half to be \"a sporadically enjoyable comedy\", but found the second half to be \"less enjoying\": \"The film leaves a lot to be desired, but a star is re-born\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/simmba-movie-review-rohit-shetty-film-leaves-a-lot-to-be-desired-but-a-star-is-re-born-1986835.html|title=Simmba Movie Review: Rohit Shetty Film Leaves a Lot to be Desired, But a Star is Re-born|website=News18}}</ref> Uday Bhatia of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' concurred with Masand: but credited Singh for playing his \"cardboard creation\" of a character with an \"underlying sweetness that renders it more winsome than the humourless masculinity of Devgan's Singham\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Consumer/ICrn1m7VU6y6Zv7kezOgJL/Simmba-movie-review-Crash-and-Burn.html|title='Simmba' movie review: Crash and Burn|last=Bhatia|first=Uday|date=28 December 2018|website=Live mint|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe box office collection figures for opening weekend of the film as presented on Bollywood Hungama are: First day It earned {{INR|link=yes}}20.72 crore nett in India which made it Singh's highest-opening film as of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/simmba-box-office-collection-day-1-film-emerges-as-ranveer-singhs-highest-opener-till-date-earns-ove-1969784|title=Simmba Box Office Collection Day 1: Film Emerges As Ranveer Singh's Highest Opener Till Date, Earns Over Rs 20 Crore|website=NDTV.com|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref> On second day it collected {{INR}}23.33 crore nett and {{INR}}31.06 crore on third day. Total first weekend nett domestic collection was {{INR}}75.11 crore. The opening week pan-India collection was {{INR}} 150.81 crore, which made it a hit film.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=taran_adarsh|author=Taran Adarsh|date=4 January 2019|number=1081099833778233345|title=#Simmba roars and scores at the BO... Crosses \u20b9 150 cr mark in Week 1... Glowing word of mouth has converted into footfalls... Fri 20.72 cr, Sat 23.33 cr, Sun 31.06 cr, Mon 21.24 cr, Tue 28.19 cr, Wed 14.49 cr, Thu 11.78 cr. Total: \u20b9 150.81 cr. India biz. SUPER HIT.r]}}</ref>\n\nIn its second week on eighth day domestic collection was {{INR}}9.02 crore. On ninth day collection rose to {{INR}}13.32 crore. Tenth day collection is {{INR}}17.49 crore. Eleventh day collection is {{INR}}6.16. Twelfth day collection is {{INR}}6.03. Thirteen day collection is {{INR}}5.31 and ending at 4.29 crore, taking second week collection to {{INR}}61.62 crore. The domestic gross is {{INR}}308.09 crore. It becomes [[Rohit Shetty]]'s biggest hit as it beats lifetime business of [[Chennai Express]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/simmba-is-rohit-shetty-s-biggest-hit-ranveer-singh-film-beats-lifetime-business-of-chennai-express-here-are-10-records-it-broke/story-lEl9QUM5KuAKdnjqixW6dP_amp.html|title= Simmba is Rohit Shetty's biggest hit, Ranveer Singh film beats lifetime business of Chennai Express.|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film grossed {{INRConvert|92.10|c}} from overseas markets as estimated by [[Bollywood Hungama]]. The gross worldwide is {{INRconvert|400.19|c}}.<ref name=box1/> [[List of Bollywood films of 2018|It became third highest-grossing film of 2018]].\n\nIn 23 days of its release the domestic gross of the film touched the {{INR}}300 crore mark. It took 40 days for the film to gross {{INR}}350 crore worldwide.<ref name=box1/>\n\nIn Pakistan, the film has collected more than {{PKR|19 crore}} till its fifth weekend.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.entertainmentpk.com/simmba-hits-20-crore-mark-at-pakistans-box-office/|title=SIMMBA NEARING THE 20 CRORE MARK AT PAKISTAN'S BOX OFFICE!|date=29 January 2019|accessdate=29 January 2019|website=EntertainmentPK.com|author=Ali Zain}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|tt7212726}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|simmba}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/simmba/ Simmba] on [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n\n{{Rohit Shetty}}\n{{Dharma Productions}}\n{{Singham}}\n\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rohit Shetty]]\n[[Category:Cop Universe]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Telstra People's Choice Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Film spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Indian rape and revenge films]]\n[[Category:Indian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films set in Goa]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Maharashtra Police]]\n[[Category:Reliance Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape in India]]\n[[Category:Indian police films]]\n[[Category:Hindi remakes of Telugu films]]\n", "name_user": "Skumar321", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simmba"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga (Club)\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 22\n|ru_appearances1     =16\n|ru_tries1           =9\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =27\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tau.)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =25\n|ru_tries2           =6\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =18 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tau.)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 26\n|ru_appearancesA     =26\n|ru_triesA           =9\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =27\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = 25\n|ru_appearancesC     = 7\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =6\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = [[Bay of Plenty rugby league team|Bay of Plenty]]\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            = \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             = 3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\n'''George Iles''' was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland and the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] team.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in [[Te Puke]] and then again in the return match in [[Tauranga]]. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played several matches for Tauranga, including 2 Kusab's Cup matches against Te Puke drawn 6-6, and won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They then beat Whakatane in the semi final. On August 2 [[Karl Ifwersen]] brought down a team from Auckland from the Grammar Old Boys, College Rifles and Ponsonby clubs to play against a Tauranga XV captained by George Iles. The Auckland team won the match 14-8\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beat Tauranga/Good Play by the Backs\n| page =3\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXI, Issue 18778\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19240804.2.19\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. In the final of the Kusab's Cup Iles captained Tauranga to victory 17-9 over Rotorua with Iles scoring a try\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs Cup Final\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8657\n| date = 1924-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240811.2.18\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. This was just the second time Tauranga had won the cup. On August 16 Iles captained the Bay of Plenty representative team in a 11-13 loss to Opotiki and a match with Poverty Bay in Gisborne. Poverty Bay won easily by 23 points to 9 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Poverty Bay Defeats Bay of Plenty\n| page =8\n| publisher =Poverty Bay Herald, Volume L, Issue 16510\n| date = 1924-08-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/PBH19240818.2.75\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nIles continued to captain Tauranga in 1925, including matches against Te Puke in June 1925, and [[Rangitaiki]] where they won 12-5 with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He continued to play for the Cadets Old Boys club\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In 1927 he took a break from playing but not from the game. He refereed matches in the Jordan Cup senior grade and the juniors.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga (Club)\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 22\n|ru_appearances1     =16\n|ru_tries1           =9\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =27\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tau.)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =25\n|ru_tries2           =6\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =18 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tau.)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 26\n|ru_appearancesA     =26\n|ru_triesA           =9\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =27\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = 25\n|ru_appearancesC     = 7\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =6\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = [[Bay of Plenty rugby league team|Bay of Plenty]]\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            = \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             = 3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\n'''George Iles''' was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland and the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] team.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in [[Te Puke]] and then again in the return match in [[Tauranga]]. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played several matches for Tauranga, including 2 Kusab's Cup matches against Te Puke drawn 6-6, and won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They then beat Whakatane in the semi final. On August 2 [[Karl Ifwersen]] brought down a team from Auckland from the Grammar Old Boys, College Rifles and Ponsonby clubs to play against a Tauranga XV captained by George Iles. The Auckland team won the match 14-8\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beat Tauranga/Good Play by the Backs\n| page =3\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXI, Issue 18778\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19240804.2.19\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. In the final of the Kusab's Cup Iles captained Tauranga to victory 17-9 over Rotorua with Iles scoring a try\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs Cup Final\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8657\n| date = 1924-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240811.2.18\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. This was just the second time Tauranga had won the cup. On August 16 Iles captained the Bay of Plenty representative team in a 11-13 loss to Opotiki and a match with Poverty Bay in Gisborne. Poverty Bay won easily by 23 points to 9 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Poverty Bay Defeats Bay of Plenty\n| page =8\n| publisher =Poverty Bay Herald, Volume L, Issue 16510\n| date = 1924-08-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/PBH19240818.2.75\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nIles continued to captain Tauranga in 1925, including matches against Te Puke in June 1925, and [[Rangitaiki]] where they won 12-5 with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He continued to play for the Cadets Old Boys club\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBack to Rugby Union", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "Eastern Idaho State Fair", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{update|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n[[File:Eastern Idaho State Fair logo.png|thumb|200px|The current logo for the Eastern Idaho State Fair.]]\n\nThe '''Eastern Idaho State Fair''' is an [[United States|American]] [[state fair]] held annually the first week of September in [[Blackfoot, Idaho]]. It is one of two annual state fairs in Idaho; the other is the [[Western Idaho Fair]], which is held in [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], the state capital. The gates to the fairgrounds open on [[Labor Day]] weekend, the first week in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofblackfoot.org/images/PDF%20Files/CityOfBlackfootHistory.pdf|title=History of Blackfoot|date=August 14, 2014|publisher=City of Blackfoot, Idaho|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u-s-history.com/pages/h2583.html|title=History of Blackfoot, Idaho|date=September 4, 2015|publisher=Online Highways LLC|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1902 some cattle ranchers had purchased some land in hopes of putting on a [[livestock show]]. The show was given the name \"Southeastern Idaho Fair\".<ref name=\"Fair\">{{cite web|title=Fair History|url=http://www.funatthefair.com/about/fair-history/|publisher=IE Productions|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen financial hardships hit the fair in 1918, it was suspended until 1920. The [[Idaho Legislature|state legislators]] passed a Fair District Bill in 1925. The fair started out as a district fair with livestock and entertainment.  After being challenged by the [[Utah State Fair]], the officials decided to change the name of the event from \"Eastern Idaho Fair\" to \"Eastern Idaho State Fair\".<ref name=\"Fair\"/> In 1925, the fair ran for four days.\n\nThe fair was shut down in July 1942, after the United States entered [[World War II]], and the buildings at the fairground were used for storage of surplus. On December 10, a fire destroyed the commercial buildings consuming [[potatoes]] and [[coal]].<ref name=\"Fair\"/> In 1942, the Fair housed some 500 Italian prisoners, who were ordered to dig [[sugar beets]] and potatoes.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> Operations have continued since 1944.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> The [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] of [[Fort Hall, Idaho|Fort Hall]] have also influenced the Eastern Idaho State Fair: an Indian Relay Race has been held throughout the fair's history.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> The state fair has been used to promote local [[agriculture]] throughout its history, with area farmers displaying their [[produce]] and livestock to the public.<ref name=\"Fair\" />\n\n2017 marked the 115 year anniversary for the fair. It set an attendance record of 239,103 which broke the previous record set in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://idahostatejournal.com/news/local/eastern-idaho-state-fair-sets-new-attendance-record/article_8b6e410f-9ccf-5329-acf8-fec22ebe76ff.html|title=2017 Eastern Idaho State Fair sets new attendance record|last=release|first=Eastern Idaho State Fair press|work=Idaho State Journal|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Opening day==\nOne of the events held at the opening of the fair is the annual [[parade]] held in Blackfoot.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} The parade starts at the south end of Shilling Avenue and makes its way to the north end. Several local clubs and organizations, as well as representatives from local high schools, police department, fire department, businesses and dance teams, participate in the line of the parade. The parade is escorted by the local police department and fire department, sounding their horns and sirens. Local high schools, [[cheerleading]] squads, [[student council]], Junior Miss winners, dance team and some clubs have their own [[Float (parade)|floats]]. The people on these floats cheer, throw candy, and promote the fair. Businesses around town are in the parade with music, candy, and brochures advertising their business. The dance teams advertise their team, but and entertain the crowd by doing a dance while walking down the road.\n\n==Attractions==\nChinese, Japanese, Mexican, American, and Indian food is sold at the fair, including [[teriyaki]] bowls, [[Fried dough|tiger ears]], [[scone]] nuggets, [[turkey (bird)|turkey legs]], [[hamburger]]s, [[funnel cake]]s, [[curly fries]], [[ice cream]], and [[Dutch oven]] cooking. A famous meal at the fair is the \"ice cream potato\" which consists of ice cream dressed up to look like a baked potato with cheddar cheese, bacon, and sour cream as toppings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://funatthefair.com/entertainment/best-fair-food/|title=Fun at the Fair|last=Barnes|first=Tom|date=2019|website=funatthefair.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://funatthefair.com/entertainment/best-fair-food/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWeekdays at the [[grandstand]]s, [[horse races]] are held from noon until about late afternoon.\n\nAfter every few heats, the Indian relays are held. The Native American tribes have three horses each, which are taken for three laps around the track. In order to use every horse each tribe has to do a switch after taking one lap, and the man on the horse does not wait until the horse is at a dead halt. The participants in the race jump off the horse while horse is slowing down, then run and jump onto the next horse. Those who fail to jump correctly get far behind the other teams.  The horses from which they jump are sometimes unable to slow down in time, and trample the rider.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}  Many people participate in [[gambling]] on the race.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nNight time events include [[motocross]], [[bull riding]], [[rodeo]], tractor pulls, [[concerts]], and a [[demolition derby]].<ref># [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409071536/http://www.idaho-state-fair.com/headline.php Headliners.] Eastern Idaho State Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008.</ref> The concerts change every year, with different genres and performers. The 2015 edition of the fair features [[Gabriel Iglesias]] and [[Cheap Trick]] as headline performers.<ref>{{cite web|author=Journal Staff|title=Gabriel Iglesias, Cheap Trick to perform at Eastern Idaho State Fair|url=http://www.idahostatejournal.com/news/local/gabriel-iglesias-cheap-trick-to-perform-at-eastern-idaho-state/article_4fb844cc-0a41-11e5-b707-2b73ce249906.html|publisher=[[Idaho State Journal]]|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern Idaho State Fair Announces New Themes, Big Acts|url=http://www.kpvi.com/mostpopular/story/Eastern-Idaho-State-Fair-Announces-New-Themes-Big/7XgUWZIYtkuJ7yjrFM_Jfg.cspx|publisher=[[KPVI-DT|KPVI News 6]]|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908054640/http://www.kpvi.com/mostpopular/story/Eastern-Idaho-State-Fair-Announces-New-Themes-Big/7XgUWZIYtkuJ7yjrFM_Jfg.cspx|archive-date=September 8, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn two other small stages, smaller events take place. Some of the smaller events include [[hypnotist]]s, [[arm wrestling]] contests, \"[[American Idol|Idaho Idol]]\" (sponsored by [[KFTZ|KFTZ \"Z-103.FM\"]]), local dance teams, singing, and comedy shows. Other events surrounding the stage include a [[petting zoo]], camp trailers, and a reptile show.\n\nFairground rides and games are operated at the show, including child rides and adult rides, including the Zipper, Fun Slide, House of Mirrors, and trucks that go around on a track. Tickets and wristbands are sold to the rides and the games. The rides are provided by [[Butler Amusements]].\n\nAnimals displayed at the fair include dairy and [[beef cattle]], different types and breeds of horses, [[sheep]], [[pig]]s, [[goat]]s, [[chicken]], [[rabbit]]s, and [[ostrich]]es.<ref name=Fair/> The public is allowed to showcase their livestock for the [[4H]] program.\n\nBuildings on the fairgrounds include agricultural information, advertising of [[hot tub]]s, trailers, fireplaces, siding for houses, and others. The smaller buildings may contain craft items. Blankets, handmade clothes, and other stitching work is displayed, along with photography of animals, nature, children, weddings, families, senior pictures, and other subjects.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Western Idaho Fair]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.funatthefair.com/}}\n* Alexander, L . [https://web.archive.org/web/20071102112247/http://www.pocatelloshops.com/blogs/art_ent.php?id=3490 \"Big Concerts and Small This Week.\"] September 5, 2007.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409071531/http://www.idaho-state-fair.com/food.php Food.] Eastern Idaho Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008\n*  Eastern Idaho State Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008\n* [http://idaho.casinocity.com/blackfoot/eastern-idaho-state-fairgrounds/ Eastern Idaho State Fairgrounds.] Casino City. 20 March 2012.\n\n{{Idaho}}\n\n{{Coord|43.19472222|-112.34055556|format=dms|display=title|type:event_region:US-ID}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bingham County, Idaho]]\n[[Category:State fairs|Idaho]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Idaho]]\n[[Category:September events]]\n[[Category:Festivals established in 1902]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{update|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n[[File:Eastern Idaho State Fair logo.png|thumb|200px|The current logo for the Eastern Idaho State Fair.]]\n\nThe '''Eastern Idaho State Fair''' is an [[United States|American]] [[state fair]] held annually the first week of September in [[Blackfoot, Idaho]]. It is one of two annual state fairs in Idaho; the other is the [[Western Idaho Fair]], which is held in [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], the state capital. The gates to the fairgrounds open on [[Labor Day]] weekend, the first week in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofblackfoot.org/images/PDF%20Files/CityOfBlackfootHistory.pdf|title=History of Blackfoot|date=August 14, 2014|publisher=City of Blackfoot, Idaho|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u-s-history.com/pages/h2583.html|title=History of Blackfoot, Idaho|date=September 4, 2015|publisher=Online Highways LLC|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1902 some cattle ranchers had purchased some land in hopes of putting on a [[livestock show]]. The show was given the name \"Southeastern Idaho Fair\".<ref name=\"Fair\">{{cite web|title=Fair History|url=http://www.funatthefair.com/about/fair-history/|publisher=IE Productions|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen financial hardships hit the fair in 1918, it was suspended until 1920. The [[Idaho Legislature|state legislators]] passed a Fair District Bill in 1925. The fair started out as a district fair with livestock and entertainment.  After being challenged by the [[Utah State Fair]], the officials decided to change the name of the event from \"Eastern Idaho Fair\" to \"Eastern Idaho State Fair\".<ref name=\"Fair\"/> In 1925, the fair ran for four days.\n\nThe fair was shut down in July 1942, after the United States entered [[World War II]], and the buildings at the fairground were used for storage of surplus. On December 10, a fire destroyed the commercial buildings consuming [[potatoes]] and [[coal]].<ref name=\"Fair\"/> In 1942, the Fair housed some 500 Italian prisoners, who were ordered to dig [[sugar beets]] and potatoes.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> Operations have continued since 1944.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> The [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] of [[Fort Hall, Idaho|Fort Hall]] have also influenced the Eastern Idaho State Fair: an Indian Relay Race has been held throughout the fair's history.<ref name=\"Fair\" /> The state fair has been used to promote local [[agriculture]] throughout its history, with area farmers displaying their [[produce]] and livestock to the public.<ref name=\"Fair\" />\n\n2017 marked the 115 year anniversary for the fair. It set an attendance record of 239,103 which broke the previous record set in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://idahostatejournal.com/news/local/eastern-idaho-state-fair-sets-new-attendance-record/article_8b6e410f-9ccf-5329-acf8-fec22ebe76ff.html|title=2017 Eastern Idaho State Fair sets new attendance record|last=release|first=Eastern Idaho State Fair press|work=Idaho State Journal|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Opening day==\nOne of the events held at the opening of the fair is the annual [[parade]] held in Blackfoot.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} The parade starts at the south end of Shilling Avenue and makes its way to the north end. Several local clubs and organizations, as well as representatives from local high schools, police department, fire department, businesses and dance teams, participate in the line of the parade. The parade is escorted by the local police department and fire department, sounding their horns and sirens. Local high schools, [[cheerleading]] squads, [[student council]], Junior Miss winners, dance team and some clubs have their own [[Float (parade)|floats]]. The people on these floats cheer, throw candy, and promote the fair. Businesses around town are in the parade with music, candy, and brochures advertising their business. The dance teams advertise their team, but and entertain the crowd by doing a dance while walking down the road.\n\n==Attractions==\nChinese, Japanese, Mexican, American, and Indian food is sold at the fair, including [[teriyaki]] bowls, [[Fried dough|tiger ears]], [[scone]] nuggets, [[turkey (bird)|turkey legs]], [[hamburger]]s, [[funnel cake]]s, [[curly fries]], [[ice cream]], and [[Dutch oven]] cooking. A famous meal at the fair is the \"ice cream potato\" which consists of ice cream dressed up to look like a baked potato with chedder cheese, bacon, and sour cream as toppings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://funatthefair.com/entertainment/best-fair-food/|title=Fun at the Fair|last=Barnes|first=Tom|date=2019|website=funatthefair.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://funatthefair.com/entertainment/best-fair-food/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWeekdays at the [[grandstand]]s, [[horse races]] are held from noon until about late afternoon.\n\nAfter every few heats, the Indian relays are held. The Native American tribes have three horses each, which are taken for three laps around the track. In order to use every horse each tribe has to do a switch after taking one lap, and the man on the horse does not wait until the horse is at a dead halt. The participants in the race jump off the horse while horse is slowing down, then run and jump onto the next horse. Those who fail to jump correctly get far behind the other teams.  The horses from which they jump are sometimes unable to slow down in time, and trample the rider.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}  Many people participate in [[gambling]] on the race.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nNight time events include [[motocross]], [[bull riding]], [[rodeo]], tractor pulls, [[concerts]], and a [[demolition derby]].<ref># [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409071536/http://www.idaho-state-fair.com/headline.php Headliners.] Eastern Idaho State Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008.</ref> The concerts change every year, with different genres and performers. The 2015 edition of the fair features [[Gabriel Iglesias]] and [[Cheap Trick]] as headline performers.<ref>{{cite web|author=Journal Staff|title=Gabriel Iglesias, Cheap Trick to perform at Eastern Idaho State Fair|url=http://www.idahostatejournal.com/news/local/gabriel-iglesias-cheap-trick-to-perform-at-eastern-idaho-state/article_4fb844cc-0a41-11e5-b707-2b73ce249906.html|publisher=[[Idaho State Journal]]|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern Idaho State Fair Announces New Themes, Big Acts|url=http://www.kpvi.com/mostpopular/story/Eastern-Idaho-State-Fair-Announces-New-Themes-Big/7XgUWZIYtkuJ7yjrFM_Jfg.cspx|publisher=[[KPVI-DT|KPVI News 6]]|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908054640/http://www.kpvi.com/mostpopular/story/Eastern-Idaho-State-Fair-Announces-New-Themes-Big/7XgUWZIYtkuJ7yjrFM_Jfg.cspx|archive-date=September 8, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn two other small stages, smaller events take place. Some of the smaller events include [[hypnotist]]s, [[arm wrestling]] contests, \"[[American Idol|Idaho Idol]]\" (sponsored by [[KFTZ|KFTZ \"Z-103.FM\"]]), local dance teams, singing, and comedy shows. Other events surrounding the stage include a [[petting zoo]], camp trailers, and a reptile show.\n\nFairground rides and games are operated at the show, including child rides and adult rides, including the Zipper, Fun Slide, House of Mirrors, and trucks that go around on a track. Tickets and wristbands are sold to the rides and the games. The rides are provided by [[Butler Amusements]].\n\nAnimals displayed at the fair include dairy and [[beef cattle]], different types and breeds of horses, [[sheep]], [[pig]]s, [[goat]]s, [[chicken]], [[rabbit]]s, and [[ostrich]]es.<ref name=Fair/> The public is allowed to showcase their livestock for the [[4H]] program.\n\nBuildings on the fairgrounds include agricultural information, advertising of [[hot tub]]s, trailers, fireplaces, siding for houses, and others. The smaller buildings may contain craft items. Blankets, handmade clothes, and other stitching work is displayed, along with photography of animals, nature, children, weddings, families, senior pictures, and other subjects.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Western Idaho Fair]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.funatthefair.com/}}\n* Alexander, L . [https://web.archive.org/web/20071102112247/http://www.pocatelloshops.com/blogs/art_ent.php?id=3490 \"Big Concerts and Small This Week.\"] September 5, 2007.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409071531/http://www.idaho-state-fair.com/food.php Food.] Eastern Idaho Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008\n*  Eastern Idaho State Fair. IE Productions. 20 Feb 2008\n* [http://idaho.casinocity.com/blackfoot/eastern-idaho-state-fairgrounds/ Eastern Idaho State Fairgrounds.] Casino City. 20 March 2012.\n\n{{Idaho}}\n\n{{Coord|43.19472222|-112.34055556|format=dms|display=title|type:event_region:US-ID}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bingham County, Idaho]]\n[[Category:State fairs|Idaho]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Idaho]]\n[[Category:September events]]\n[[Category:Festivals established in 1902]]\n", "name_user": "Narky Blert", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_Idaho_State_Fair"}
{"title_page": "Simon (surname)", "text_new": "'''Simon''' is a [[patronymic]] surname deriving from [[Simon (given name)]]. It is also a [[surname]] of [[Old Norse]] origins and a variant of [[Sigmund]], a [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] [[given name]] with roots in proto-Germanic [[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Germanic/segaz|''*segaz'']] and [[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Germanic/mund\u014d|''*mund\u014d'']], giving a rough translation of \"protection through victory\".<ref>{{cite book |last= Gauch\u00e9 |first= Isebell |title= The A to Z of Names (Revised and Expanded Edition) : Discover the promise your name holds |publisher= Struik Christian Media |location= Cape Town |year= 2012 |isbn= 1415316260 |id= lemma: Siegmund }}</ref> Notable people with this surname include:\n\n{{compact ToC|side=yes|top=yes|num=yes}}\n\n==A==\n* [[Abbey Simon]] (1920\u20132019), Jewish-American pianist\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Simon (wine)]] (1877\u20131970), French wine expert \n* [[Andr\u00e9 Simon (racing driver)]] (1920\u20132012), former French racing car driver\n* [[Anne Simon]], American science advisor on the TV series ''The X-Files''\n\n==B==\n* [[Barry Simon]] (born 1946), American mathematical physicist\n* [[Barry Simon (politician)]] (1936\u20132004), Australian politician\n* [[Ben Simon]] (born 1978), American ice hockey player\n* [[Bill Simon (politician)]] (born 1951), American businessman and politician\n* [[Bill Simon (musician)]] (born 1920), American jazz musician\n* [[Bob Simon]] (1941\u20132015), American correspondent on CBS News\n\n==C==\n* [[Calvin Simon]] (born 1942), American musician\n* [[Carlos Eug\u00eanio Simon]] (born 1965), Brazilian FIFA football referee\n* [[Carly Simon]] (born 1945), American singer-songwriter/musician\n* [[Chase Simon]] (born 1989), American basketball player for [[Maccabi Ashdod B.C.|Maccabi Ashdod]] of the [[Israeli Basketball Premier League]]\n* [[Chris Simon]] (born 1972), Canadian ice hockey player\n* [[Claude Simon]] (1913\u20132005), French novelist\n* [[Cliff Simon]] (1962), South African athlete and actor\n* [[Corey Simon]] (born 1977), former American football player\n* [[Cosette Simon]], American politician\n\n==D==\n* [[Danny Simon]] (1918\u20132005), American television writer\n* [[David Simon (basketball)]] (born 1982), American basketball player\n* [[David Simon (CEO)]], American CEO of Simon Property Group\n* [[David Simon, Baron Simon of Highbury]] (born 1935), British businessman\n* [[David Simon (writer)]] (born 1960), American author and journalist\n* Dean Simon (born 1960), American professional wrestler better known as [[Dean Malenko]]\n* [[Dick Simon]] (born 1933), former American racing driver\n* [[Dick Simon (entrepreneur)]] (born 1953), American entrepreneur, philanthropist, photographer and speaker\n* [[Diederik Simon]] (born 1970), Dutch rower\n* [[Diosdado Sim\u00f3n]] (1954-2002), Spanish biologist\n\n==E==\n* [[Edgardo Simon]] (born 1974), Argentinian track and road cyclist\n* [[Edward Simon (musician)]]\n* [[Edward Simon (choreographer)]]\n* [[Eleazar ben Simon]], 1st century Zealot leader\n* [[\u00c9milie Simon]] (born 1978), French singer and composer\n* [[Ernst Simon]] (1899\u20131988), German-Israeli Jewish educator\n* [[Ernst Julius Walter Simon]] (1893\u20131981), British Sinologist\n* [[Eug\u00e8ne Simon]] (1848\u20131924), French arachnologist\n\n==F==\n* [[Francesca Simon]] (born 1955), Anglo-American author\n* [[Francis Simon]] (born Franz Eugen Simon) (1893\u20131956), German/British physical chemist\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois G\u00e9rard|Fran\u00e7ois Pascal Simon, Baron G\u00e9rard]] (1770\u20131837), French painter\n\n==G==\n* [[Geroy Simon]] (born 1975), Canadian footballer\n* [[Glyn Simon]] (1903\u201372), Archbishop of Wales (1968\u201371)\n* [[Gilles Simon]] (born 1984), French tennis player\n* [[G\u00fcnther Simon]] (1925\u201372), East German actor\n* [[Gustav Simon]] (1900\u201345), German Chief of the Civil Administration in Nazi occupied Luxembourg  (1940\u201345)\n* [[Gustav Simon (physician)]] (1824\u201376), German surgeon\n\n==H==\n* [[Harry Simon (boxer)]] (born 1972), Namibian boxer\n* [[Harry Simon (sport shooter)]] (1873\u20131932), American sport shooter\n* [[Helmut Simon]], German discoverer of \u00d6tzi the Iceman\n* [[Henri Simon]] (1866\u20131956). French army officer\n* [[Herbert A. Simon]] (1916\u20132001), American cognitive psychologist and polymath\n* [[Herbert Simon (real estate)]] (born 1934), American real estate developer\n\n==I==\n* [[Ingo Simon]] (1875-1964), English archer, singer, and writer\n\n==J==\n* [[Jean-Claude Simon]] (born 1948), French research scientist\n* [[Jeanne Hurley Simon]] (1922-2000), American politician\n* [[Jed Simon]] (born 1964), Canadian musician\n* [[Jocelyn Simon, Baron Simon of Glaisdale]] (1911\u20132006), British politician and QC\n* Jody Simon (born 1956), American professional wrestler better known as [[Joe Malenko]]\n* [[Joe Simon]] (1913\u20132011), Jewish-American comic book writer\n* [[Joe Simon (musician)]] (born 1943), American soul and R&B artist\n* [[John Simon (disambiguation)|John Simon]] various, including :\n** [[John Simon (critic)|John Simon]] (1925\u20132019), American author and literary, film and drama critic\n** [[John Simon (record producer)]] (born 1941), American record producer for [[Columbia Records]]\n** Sir [[John Simon (doctor)]] (1816\u20131904), Chief Medical Officer for England, 1855\u201376\n** [[John L. Simon]] (Jack Simon), U.S. national swimming coach\n* [[J. Minos Simon|Joseph Minos Simon]] (1922\u20132004), American attorney\n* [[Josef Simon]] (1930\u20132016), German philosopher\n* [[Joseph Simon]] (1851\u20131935), German-born American politician\n* [[Josette Simon]] (born 1960), British actress\n* [[Joshua Simon]], Israeli art curator and journalist from Tel Aviv\n* [[Jules Simon]] (1814\u201396), French statesman and philosopher\n* [[Juli\u00e1n Sim\u00f3n]] (born 1987), Spanish motorcycle racer\n* [[Julian Lincoln Simon]] (193